<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Florence Lingers Off N.C.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Hurricane Florence weakened into a tropical storm
Wednesday, a day after being blamed for at least two deaths in
North Carolina, and forecasters said it could soon post a threat to
Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Florence, which had sustained winds of 70 mph, could regenerate
into a hurricane as it slowly moves away from the United States,
forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Florence will have an opportunity to re-strengthen to
hurricane status once it begins to move away from its present
location toward warmer waters,'' said Lixion Avila, a hurricane
specialist at the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Avila said Bermuda should monitor Florence's progress and a
hurricane watch may be required early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At 11 p.m. Wednesday, Florence, the sixth named storm of the
2000 Atlantic hurricane season, was about 525 miles west-southwest
of Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Strong rip currents associated with the hurricane caught
swimmers by surprise Tuesday at Kure Beach, N.C., and a man and a
woman died. Seven other people had to be rescued. Another man was
missing after falling out of a kayak at Carolina Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The two beaches remained closed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters were also watching a system in the Caribbean that
could become a tropical depression within the next 24 hours, Blake
said. It is located southeast of Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula and is
moving to the northwest between 10 mph and 15 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
