<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Delays Rebel Actions  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- The government is considering
imposing a news blackout on the prolonged hostage crisis involving
Muslim rebels in the southern Philippines, an official said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Alexander Aguirre's comments follow
suggestions from other Philippine officials that the government is
considering a military attack on the Abu Sayyaf rebels. The rebels,
who have been holding hostages for months, recently released many
of them in exchange for millions of dollars but then angered the
government by kidnapping three more people from a Malaysian diving
resort Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will endorse the idea of a non-reporting of the operational
matters or matters that will prejudice national interest,'' Aguirre
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the government should announce general actions involving
the hostage crisis but details should be kept secret to protect
government operations.
</P>
<P>
   The latest kidnapping, following a promise by the guerrillas not
to take any more hostages while negotiations are under way, was
seen as a defiance of the government. However, during a high-level
Cabinet meeting Wednesday chaired by President Joseph Estrada, the
government opted to hold off for now on tougher steps -- including a
military attack.
</P>
<P>
   The abduction in Malaysia followed the release Saturday of four
Europeans, the last foreigners from a group of 21 hostages taken in
April from another Malaysian resort. The rebels have been holding
their captives on Jolo, an island in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The government said Thursday it is giving responsibility for
negotiations for the three Malaysians to local officials on Jolo
instead of to a special negotiating team that handled the earlier
abductions. The team has been criticized for paying huge ransoms to
the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf are also holding one Filipino captured in April,
two French television journalists, an American Muslim and 12
Filipino Christian evangelists. The rebels claim they are fighting
for an independent Islamic state in the impoverished southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations for the remaining hostages have been suspended
because of fighting among Abu Sayyaf factions over the division of
ransom money. Negotiators say about $15 million in ransom has been
paid so far, about $10 million of it by Libya.
</P>
<P>
   The abduction of the three new hostages has sparked fears of
another wave of kidnappings encouraged by the large ransom
payments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 0047 </TRAILER>
