<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Rejects Tax Concessions  </HEADLINE>
By JILL LAWLESS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Britons awoke Thursday to eerily empty roads,
depleted supermarket shelves -- and troops on standby, a sign of
Prime Minister Tony Blair's hardened resolve not to give in to
protesters angry over high fuel taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said ''lives are at risk'' from the protesters, whose
weeklong demonstrations outside fuel depots and refineries have
left gasoline pumps bone-dry and disrupted schools, hospitals,
businesses and transportation across Britain.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign the crisis may be winding down, a key group of
protesters announced Thursday morning it was ending its refinery
picket.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have backed down. We have won the moral issue,'' said
Brynle Williams, spokesman for protesters at the Stanlow refinery
in northwest England. He called on other demonstrators across the
country to end their pickets and join in a national campaign for a
cut in fuel tax.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came hours after Blair went on television for a
second night to appeal for an end to the protests.
</P>
<P>
   ''Real damage is now being done to real people,'' Blair said
Wednesday evening. He blamed protesters for fuel shortages that
have triggered school closings, delayed non-vital surgery in
hospitals and even threatened deliveries by Britain's famously
reliable Royal Mail.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not just schools, but teachers, police, firemen -- the
employees on whom our public services depend,'' Blair said. ''Lives
are at risk if those people can't get to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair's no-surrender stance was echoed by leaders in Belgium and
Germany, where fuel protesters have also snarled traffic and
targeted political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In London, scores of trucks were stopped by police Wednesday on
Park Lane, home to some of the city's most expensive hotels, as
drivers tried to converge on Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's gas prices average $4.31 a gallon, with taxes
accounting for three-quarters of the cost, and polls show that a
majority of the public supports the protesters. But signs of
fatigue are setting in as the country contemplates a weekend
without crucial goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   ''Enough is enough,'' advised a front-page editorial in
Thursday's edition of the mass-market Mirror newspaper. ''No fuel
protest, however justified, is worth the loss of a single life,''
it said. The tabloid Mail called on protesters to ''end your
blockade today, while you still hold the moral high ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The government, granted emergency powers to deal with the
crisis, deployed about 80 military fuel tankers to strategic points
across the country Wednesday night, the Ministry of Defense said.
</P>
<P>
   Health Secretary Alan Milburn said he had ordered National
Health Service administrators to have emergency plans in place.
Late Wednesday, the National Blood Authority also went on alert,
saying it feared its blood supplies could soon be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Peter Davis, CEO of the Sainsbury's supermarket chain, said
his stores would be out of food in ''days rather than weeks'' as
buyers rushed to stock up on milk, bread and other essentials.
</P>
<P>
   Some fuel did trickle back to service stations Wednesday. About
500 tankers left refineries and depots, many under police escort.
Some truck drivers refused to cross protest lines, citing fears for
their safety.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day there would be at least 3,000 tanker deliveries
in Britain, the Petrol Retailers Association said.
</P>
<P>
   Most gas stations remained closed, with Esso saying the ''vast
majority'' of its 1,620 stations were shut and Shell reporting that
only 30 of its 1,100 garages had gas.
</P>
<P>
   Although Britain has been hardest hit, other European countries,
including France, Belgium, Germany and the Netherlands, have
experienced traffic-snarling protests in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, where fuel taxes are slated to rise at the start of
the year, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder was targeted by angry
protesters when he visited the northern city of Schwerin.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder warned that the protests would only hurt Germany's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Drop this dangerous game, because it could threaten the growth
an employment prospects we currently have,'' he said. But the
national truckers association called for new protests later this
month to slow traffic on the autobahn.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian Prime Minister Guy Verhofstadt also refused demands
Wednesday for a fuel-tax rebate for the trucking industry, even as
protests expanded to major freeways and border points.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, Blair insisted he would not be pressured into
lowering fuel taxes, saying that would shatter his government's
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever the protesters do ... it cannot be right to try to
force a change in policy by these means,'' he said. ''We will not
be intimidated. We will not give into violence, to blockades, to
threats.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, too, said they would not back down.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we leave now then everything we have done will be for
nothing,'' said Mark Williams, a spokesman for the protesters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
