</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A jet carrying Pakistan's military ruler and 120 other
people bound for England and Pakistan was forced to return to John F. Kennedy
International Airport late Wednesday after a bomb threat. No injuries were
reported. The threat was received by telephone after Pakistan International
Airlines Flight 722 left the airport, Port Authority spokesman Alan Hicks said.
Pakistan's military ruler, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, was on the plane, said Maleeha
Lodhi, Pakistan's ambassador to the United States who was with him in New York.
She said the flight was expected to be delayed three to four hours.
