<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plane carrying Pakistani ruler forced to return to JFK after bomb threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A jetliner carrying Pakistani military ruler
Pervez Musharraf returned to John F. Kennedy International Airport
late Wednesday because of a bomb threat.
</P>
<P>
   The flight was expected to be delayed by several hours, said
Maleeha Lodhi, Pakistan's ambassador to the United States, who
spoke with The Associated Press by telephone after the plane
landed. Lodhi, who said she was with Musharraf during the
interview, confirmed that he had been aboard the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Port Authority spokesman Alan Hicks said Musharraf was safely
removed from the plane and was in a secure area of the airport
early Thursday. The 120 other passengers and crew that were on
board the Boeing 747 were also safely removed from the plane, and
were in the process of identifying their luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said a 911 call was received in New York at 9 p.m.
Wednesday, just as Pakistan International Airlines Flight 722 was
in position to take off. The call warned that three bombs had been
placed on the plane and that they were set to detonate upon
takeoff, Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot was informed of the threat, but determined that it was
safe to take off because the plane and luggage had already been
swept by bomb-sniffing dog units of the New York Police Department,
the Port Authority Police Department and the Secret Service, Hicks
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane was flying near Boston, the pilot decided that the
plane should be re-examined and returned to Kennedy Airport. When
it landed in New York, at about 10:15 p.m., it was moved to a
remote area of the airport's tarmac, and all passengers were
removed from the plane, Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said the luggage, which was placed on the tarmac, was
being matched to the passengers and crew to make sure there were no
unclaimed pieces. Bomb-sniffing dogs would be used again after all
pieces were identified, Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected the passengers to re-board the plane once
the process was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan International Airlines Flight 722 was scheduled to fly
to Manchester, England, and then continue on to Karachi, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf took over the leadership of Pakistan last October
after the military deposed Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in a
bloodless coup.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf has vowed to cleanse the country's politics of
corruption before holding elections - a decision that has been
widely welcomed by people in Pakistan, though it has drawn
criticism abroad. Pakistan's Supreme Court has given the
military-led government three years to complete the task and return
the country to democracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
