Japan Says Economy Recovering
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Surging oil prices could hamper Japan's progress towards a
solid recovery from its decade-long economic slowdown, the government warned in
a monthly report Thursday. The Economic Planning Agency left its overall
assessment of the economy unchanged in September for the third straight month,
saying that ''movements toward a self-sustaining recovery centered on the
business sector continue.'' But Haruhito Arai, director of the Economic Planning
Agency's domestic research bureau, said the impact of rising oil prices on Asian
economies could threaten the outlook for Japanese exports.
</P>
