<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child Malnutrition Plagues Iraq  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- A U.N. report says child malnutrition remains a
serious problem in much of Iraq despite increases in food rations
in the country, which has been under U.N. sanctions for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Rome-based Food and Agriculture Organization released the
report Wednesday, two days after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
said in New York that Iraqi officials have refused to cooperate
with an investigation of the humanitarian situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's report was based on a mission to Iraq in May by
officials from FAO and two other U.N. agencies, the World Food
Program and the World Health Organization. The agencies said the
report was prepared for the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that two straight years of drought and
inadequate availability of seeds and other farming supplies
severely hurt Iraqi agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Annan had noted that under the U.N. oil-for-food program, which
allows Iraq to sell oil to help feed its population, Iraqi
officials have considerably increased the amount of food getting to
ordinary people. But, he said, the Baghdad government has indicated
it has no plans to cooperate with a panel of experts charged with
making a comprehensive report on the overall humanitarian situation
there.
</P>
<P>
   FAO officials in Rome could not say if Annan's remarks were
based on some of the report's findings.
</P>
<P>
   The May mission found that food rations are lacking in
vegetables, fruit and animal products and that monthly rations only
last up to three weeks. The mission urged Iraq for ''timely
submission of applications'' for food contracts, which then must be
approved by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait. Sanctions can be lifted only after U.N. weapons inspectors
report that Baghdad is free of its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 0203 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000914.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wen Ho Lee Comes Home To Party  </HEADLINE>
By HEATHER CLARK
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- From traitor to hero, Wen Ho Lee was
driven from solitary confinement to a homecoming with American
flags, Chinese food and a crush of friends.
</P>
<P>
   ''I need to say thank you to everybody who supported me, and I
want to say thank you to all the neighbors,'' Lee told a crowd of
about 200 who greeted him at his home hours after he was released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   One man held up a banner reading ''You won!!!'' as news
helicopters hovered overhead. A sign on the back of a car near
Lee's home said, ''Welcome home to your town, your garden and
Mozart.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheered and clapped and broke into rounds of ''For
He's a Jolly Good Fellow'' as Lee beamed. They also gave a round of
applause to his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 60, was at the center of one of the nation's most important
government secrecy cases in years. He pleaded guilty Wednesday to a
single count of mishandling nuclear secrets and the government
dropped 58 other counts.
</P>
<P>
   After he'd been freed in Albuquerque, Lee told reporters: ''The
next few days, I'm going fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors apparently knew of his hobby. A couple of blocks from
the Lee house, Birgit and Patrick McGaughey hung out a sign that
said, ''Go Fish,'' and another proclaiming, ''A Bad Day Fishing is
Better Than a Good Day Working,'' next to a fishing pole.
</P>
<P>
   Once he arrived home, Lee changed from the suit he'd worn in
court into a blue polo shirt and slacks and went next door to a
party thrown by his longtime friends and Los Alamos National
Laboratory colleagues, Don and Jean Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very happy to be home. I'm so impressed with the big crowd
here,'' he told those gathered in the Marshalls' back yard. ''The
last nine months were pretty tough for me but I survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese food, cold cuts and fruit were spread out on a pingpong
table in the Marshalls' yard. Police cordoned off the neighborhood
for the block party.
</P>
<P>
   ''He needs the celebration -- we all need the celebration. The
tension has just been incredible,'' neighbor Mary Norris said.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Marshall said defense lawyers told Lee they were not going
to accept payment from him -- but they wanted a fishing trip and a
gourmet meal. She also urged journalists to ''get acquainted with
Wen Ho as we know him. He is a fun guy and you're going to love
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The scientist, meanwhile, has some catching up to do around the
house. Lee's son Chung said the family's yard could use some help
from his dad now that he's home.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a great landscaper so we'll try to get him busy on that.
And we'll definitely try to get him fishing,'' Chung Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Lee: http://www.wenholee.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
