<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani: Before you drink bottled water, sniff it  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Authorities were investigating whether three
incidents in which people were sickened after drinking contaminated
bottled water were the result of tampering.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, joined
by Police Commissioner Bernard Kerik and members of the Federal
Bureau of Investigation, said all three victims had recovered after
being treated at area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said New Yorkers should not be alarmed, but warned that
people should be especially careful in drinking bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   ''Make sure that you open the bottle yourself,'' he said. ''And
you actually hear it, and you hear the noise and the air coming
out.'' Giuliani added that people should open their own bottles of
water in restaurants and that they should sniff it before drinking.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 3, a woman felt a burning sensation in her throat and
began bleeding from the mouth after drinking bottled water in a
restaurant. Tests on the water showed that it contained ''some type
of sodium hydroxide,'' Kerik said. Kerik described it as a ''strong
cleaning agent'' or a ''lye-type agent.''
</P>
<P>
   A man who drank from a bottle of water purchased from a midtown
deli on Aug. 27 felt a burning sensation in his throat. The water
was found to contain ammonia.
</P>
<P>
   The last case was on Sept. 6, when a woman gave her 18-month-old
son a sip of bottled water purchased from a takeout restaurant. The
baby became ill and the water turned out to be tainted with
ammonia.
</P>
<P>
   All three cases involved different brands of water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-14-00 0228 </TRAILER>
