<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Gains 81; Dow Falls 12  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading Thursday
after the government reported an unexpected drop in wholesale
prices during August.
</P>
<P>
   The news reaffirmed assessments that the economy is slowing and
that the Federal Reserve won't need to raise interest rates in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 11.84 to 11,170.34 in the
first hour of trading. The Nasdaq composite index was up 81.24 at
3,975.13, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 7.47to 1,492.38.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street got a lift from the Labor Department's report that
wholesale prices fell an unexpected 0.2 percent last month, the
first drop in four months. The decline followed a flat reading in
the Producer Price Index in July.
</P>
<P>
   The report was further evidence that the economy is slowing and
reassured investors that the inflation-wary Fed is unlikely to
raise rates for a seventh time since June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks led the market higher Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle traded up $3.19 at $85 after a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
analyst upgraded the stock to ''strong buy'' from ''outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose $1.25 to $62.50, gaining back some of the ground it
lost after an investment firm ratings downgrade on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems was up $1.44 at $62.75.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 149.28 million
shares, compared to 149.51 million on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 4.15 to 538.16.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.14 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.00 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up1.21 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
1.18 percent.
</P>
