<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic Challenger Gets Pelted  </HEADLINE>
By ELENA BECATOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) --Slobodan Milosevic's
supporters threw stones, eggs and tomatoes at his strongest
challenger in upcoming elections, striking him in the face as he
tried to address a rally Thursday in this divided Kosovo city.
</P>
<P>
   The rally in Kosovska Mitrovica was intended to be a moment of
glory for Vojislav Kostunica, who was touring the isolated Serb
enclaves in a bid to win votes. Instead, the soft-spoken law
professor faced a mostly male crowd largely uninterested in the
message that he was the man who could beat Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ''He (Milosevic) put you up to this -- God will forgive you but
God will not forgive him,'' Kostunica managed to say to his
attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Security guards tried to shelter him from the melee and
surrounded him as he tried to speak. After a few futile attempts to
speak, the bodyguards then pushed him off the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's supporters then grew more violent, attacking
Kostunica's convoy and smashing windshields. Kostunica was hit with
a rock below his eye, but the cut did not appear serious.
Bodyguards managed to pull him away.
</P>
<P>
   Riots are common in Kosovska Mitrovica, a town divided by the
Ibar River into a southern ethnic Albanian side and a predominantly
Serb northern part. Thursday's action, however, pitted Serb against
Serb.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of Sept. 24 elections, Serbia is radically polarized
between Milosevic's supporters and those who oppose the autocratic
ruler. This also applies to Kosovo's Serbs. Despite a strong
following for Kostunica among the dwindling Serb population,
hard-liners and thugs retain a firm footing in this city 25 miles
north from the capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   A leader of Kosovo Serbs, Oliver Ivanovic, blamed Milosevic's
forces for causing Thursday's trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was evidently a setup, a planned action and to our dismay
we had no previous knowledge of the plan and got trapped,'' Oliver
Ivanovic told The Associated Press. He called Kostunica ''the only
Serb politician who really took to heart the plight of our people
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica had been sweeping through northern Kosovo in a
Western-style campaign tour. It was his first visit to the
U.N.-administered province during the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Though Milosevic has pledged to travel to this seat of Serb
nationalism, NATO leaders have promised to arrest him on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The top U.N. administrator in Kosovo, Bernard Kouchner, told the
French weekly Le Nouvel Observateur that he was concerned over the
elections, since the balloting ''dones not meet international
criteria.'' But he admitted the U.N. administration could do
nothing to stop it. Kosovo is still recognized as part of Serbia --
Yugoslavia's main republic -- even though the province is run by the
United Nations and NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no voter lists'' for the election, and ''the votes
will be counted outside of Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In past votes, Kosovo has proven to be a repository of stolen
ballots. No census has taken place in this province for more than a
decade and the number of eligible voters is not known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 1034 </TRAILER>
