<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Korea Official To Visit S.Korea  </HEADLINE>
By KYONG-HWA SEOK
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North Korea has reaffirmed a promised
visit to South Korea by the North's leader, Kim Jong Il, saying the
communist state's No. 2 man will visit South Korea soon to prepare
for the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came Thursday during a 4&AMP;frac12;-hour meeting between Kim
Yong Sun, a special envoy of the North Korean leader, and his South
Korean counterpart, Lim Dong-won.
</P>
<P>
   Without specifying a date, a joint statement said the North
Korean leader will visit South Korea ''in the near future.''
Unconfirmed local news reports have said Kim Jong Il will visit
Seoul next spring.
</P>
<P>
   The joint statement said Kim Yong Nam, president of the
Presidium of the North's Supreme People's Assembly, will visit
Seoul ahead of Kim Jong Il's visit. Kim Yong Nam serves as a
ceremonial head of state for the isolated North.
</P>
<P>
   The talks between the North Korean emissary and Lim also
produced a series of agreements aimed at further advancing a recent
thaw in relations between the two Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   South and North Korea will hold a Red Cross meeting Wednesday on
the scenic Diamond Mountain on the North's east coast to discuss
two more reunions of separated families by year's end, the joint
statement said. The two Koreas each allowed 100 people to cross the
Demilitarized Zone, the world's most heavily fortified border, in
August for temporary reunions with families they haven't seen since
the 1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Also, officials from both sides will meet Sept. 25 in Seoul to
sign accords to guarantee investment and avoid double taxation.
Such accords are essential to encouraging South Korean investments
in North Korea, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the sides apparently made little progress on military
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The joint statement simply reiterated an earlier agreement that
the two sides were still discussing opening the first meeting
between their defense ministers. South Korea had hoped to hold the
proposed defense chiefs' talks late this month to discuss
tension-easing measures, such as a military hot line to prevent
accidental armed skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
   The communist North's 1.1 million hard-line armed forces are
considered one of the biggest obstacles to promoting reconciliation
on the divided Korean Peninsula. Up to 2 million battle-ready
troops face each other across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Yong Sun, the North Korean envoy, arrived here Monday on a
four-day trip to follow up on a historic summit between Kim Jong Il
and South Korean President Kim Dae-jung in June. During the summit,
the two leaders agreed to work together for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Yong Sun paid a courtesy call on the Southern president on
Thursday. He returned home later in the day through the border
village of Panmunjom.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jong Il had promised to visit Seoul in return for Kim
Dae-jung's visit to Pyongyang in June. No North Korean head of
state has visited Seoul, and Kim's planned trip would be a new
milestone in improving ties.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean Peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
pro-Western South Korea in 1945. Their war in the early 1950s ended
without a peace treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 1038 </TRAILER>
