<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Police Raid Opposition  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Detectives and intelligence agents
escorted by armed paramilitary police raided offices of the main
opposition party Thursday, arresting two officials.
</P>
<P>
   A search warrant handed to the opposition party, the Movement
for Democratic Change, said police suspected three buildings in
Harare were used by the opposition to store ''arms of war.'' No
weapons were found, party secretary-general Welshman Ncube said.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition viewed the raids as a pretext to seize
information on party strategies ahead of presidential elections
next year and details of its funds so supporters and donors could
be targeted for harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ''That must be one of the reasons behind this nonsensical
operation,'' Ncube said.
</P>
<P>
   Police refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The raids came three months after the opposition party won 57 of
120 elected seats in parliamentary elections in June. The results
of the vote posed the biggest challenge to President Robert
Mugabe's hold on power since he led the nation to independence in
1980. In the outgoing parliament, Mugabe's ruling party controlled
all but three seats.
</P>
<P>
   At least 31 people died and thousands were left homeless in
political violence ahead of the elections. Most of the victims were
opposition supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Around dawn Thursday, police raided the party headquarters north
of the city center, an administrative support center in downtown
Harare and offices in the southern suburb of St. Martins around
dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Join Nkhatazo, the party's chief security officer, and an
assistant, Socks Ncube, were arrested and taken to Harare's main
police station for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers acting for the opposition prevented police from
scrutinizing documents and reading computer files in the searches,
which continued for several hours, Welshman Ncube said.
</P>
<P>
   Magistrate David Manguta's warrant allowed police to search only
for suspected weapons listed as grenades, pistols, rifles and tear
gas canisters.
</P>
<P>
   Uniformed police armed with automatic weapons remained at the
opposition offices, and Ncube said party officials suspected that
police were seeking a further warrant to seize documents and
computer data.
</P>
<P>
   Police at the downtown offices accused youth leader Nelson
Chamisa and Gandi Mudzingwa, a personal assistant to opposition
leader Morgan Tsvangirai, of gun running. Tsvangirai is out of the
country on party business.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, a grenade was hurled into the yard of the
opposition headquarters. No one was injured, and no one claimed
responsibility for the grenade attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
