<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 53; Nasdaq Rises 81  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chips drifted lower and technology stocks
moved higher for a second consecutive session Thursday after the
government reported an unexpected drop in wholesale prices during
August.
</P>
<P>
   The news reaffirmed assessments that the economy is slowing and
that the Federal Reserve won't need to raise interest rates in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 53.28 to 11,128.90 in late
morning trading. The Nasdaq composite index was up 81.01 at
3,974.90, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 5.33 to
1,490.24.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street got a lift from the Labor Department's report that
wholesale prices fell an unexpected 0.2 percent last month, the
first drop in four months. The decline followed a flat reading in
the Producer Price Index in July.
</P>
<P>
   The report was further evidence that the economy is slowing and
reassured investors that the inflation-wary Fed is unlikely to
raise rates for a seventh time since June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had some good data today for the soft-landing scenario, but
obviously there is still not enough confidence overall to get
things totally on track,'' said Ronald J. Hill, an investment
strategist and partner at Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co. ''But the
course of prices is more likely in our opinion going to go up than
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks led the market higher Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle traded up $3.50 at $85.31 after a Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter analyst upgraded the stock to ''strong buy'' from
''outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose $1.38 to $62.63, gaining back some of the ground it
lost after an investment firm ratings downgrade on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems was up $1.75 at $63.06. And Conexant Systems rose
$12.88 to $49.94, nearly a 35-percent increase, after the company
announced late Wednesday that it was spinning its Internet
infrastructure business off into a separate company.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nasdaq is playing a little catch up because they had a
serious setback of underperfomance as we got into September,'' said
Hill, the Brown Brothers Harriman analyst. ''The Dow got a big
boost because of J.P. Morgan speculation. Now that the deal is
known, there's less of a single driver that's pushing the Dow.''
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan and Chase Manhattan Bank announced Wednesday they
were merging. Morgan's shares had been inching upwards on
speculation a deal was in the works, but the announcement sent both
companies stocks down by the end of trading Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That trend continued Thursday with Morgan sliding 63 cents to
$180.63 and Chase Manhattan falling 63 cents to $50.56.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 333.69 million
shares, compared to 345.09 million on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 4.55 to 538.55.
</P>
