<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Activist Claims Innocence  </HEADLINE>
By DRAGAN ILIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIS, Yugoslavia (AP) -- An imprisoned ethnic Albanian activist --
by turns poet, pediatrician and women's rights champion -- appeared
in a Yugoslav court Thursday, said she was innocent and demanded to
see documents about her case.
</P>
<P>
   Flora Brovina, 50, whose case has become a rallying cry to free
all Albanian prisoners from Serb jails, was sentenced in December
to 12 years in prison on terrorism charges and alleged links to the
rebels of the disbanded Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented move in June, Yugoslavia's Supreme Court
overturned the conviction and referred the case back to the court
in the southern city of Nis -- a development, Brovina says
authorities never told her of.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a judge Thursday, Brovina -- looking calm and composed but
tired -- told a packed courtroom that she had found out from
newspapers of the supreme court's decision and demanded it be
handed to her and her defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am innocent and I would like to see the supreme court's
statement with my own eyes,'' Brovina said.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding judge Marina Milanovic ruled that the new trial would
begin Oct. 12 and ordered Brovina back to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Natasa Kandic of the Belgrade-based Humanitarian Law Center
rushed past police guards to embrace Brovina before the Albanian
activist was taken back to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expected Brovina to be a free woman today,'' Kandic said.
''This all is an unnecessary delay because the charges are
senseless and preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Brovina's three attorneys, Zivojin Jokanovic, said his
client was mistreated and ''deprived of her rights in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   She ''was even denied pen and paper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brovina was arrested by Serb forces during NATO's 78-day air
bombardment of Yugoslavia. NATO resorted to the bombing to end a
Serbian army crackdown in the largely ethnic Albanian province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Brovina and hundreds of other Kosovo Albanians were transferred
to prisons in Serbia proper after Yugoslav forces moved out and
NATO-led peacekeepers took control of the province.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, now run by NATO and a U.N. peace mission, remains
officially part of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   By last July, the international Red Cross registered 1,922
ethnic Albanian detainees throughout Serbia. About half of them
have since been released.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 1351 </TRAILER>
