<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 95; Nasdaq Climbs 41  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chips fell sharply Thursday on
profit-taking and concerns about the drop in the euro currency, but
technology stocks moved higher for a second straight session on
speculation about upbeat third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 95.45 to 11,128.16 in
afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index was up
40.81 at 3,934.70, but the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 1.43 to
1,483.48.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, Wall Street got a lift from the Labor
Department's report that wholesale prices fell an unexpected 0.2
percent last month, the first drop in four months. The decline
followed a flat reading in the Producer Price Index in July.
</P>
<P>
   The report was further evidence that the economy is slowing and
reassured investors that the inflation-wary Fed is unlikely to
raise rates for a seventh time since June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had some good data today for the soft-landing scenario, but
obviously there is still not enough confidence overall to get
things totally on track,'' said Ronald J. Hill, an investment
strategist and partner at Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co. ''But the
course of prices is more likely, in our opinion, going to go up
than down.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks moved higher, including Conexant Systems,
which rose $14 to $51.06, a nearly 38 percent increase. The company
announced late Wednesday it was spinning its Internet
infrastructure business off into a separate company.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle, which was expected to release earnings late Thursday,
traded up $2.25 at $84.06 after a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
analyst upgraded the stock to ''strong buy'' from ''outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems was up 19 cents at $61.50.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nasdaq is playing a little catch up because they had a
serious setback of underperfomance as we got into September,'' said
Hill, the Brown Brothers Harriman analyst. ''The Dow got a big
boost because of J.P. Morgan speculation. Now that the deal is
known, there's less of a single driver that's pushing the Dow.''
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan and Chase Manhattan Bank announced Wednesday they
were merging. Morgan's shares had been inching upwards on
speculation a deal was in the works, but the announcement sent both
companies stocks down by the end of trading Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That trend continued Thursday with Morgan sliding $1.56 on
profit-taking to $179.69 and Chase Manhattan falling $1 to $50.19.
</P>
<P>
   Colgate-Palmolive shares fell $8.56 to $47.63, a 15 percent drop
after a Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown analyst downgraded the stock,
saying European currency woes and higher fuel costs would hurt the
consumer product maker's profits. Later in the day, the company
issued a statement saying it was comfortable with third-quarter
earnings estimates, but did not offer other specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-food company McDonald's was also down, declining $1.38 to
$26.63, after it warned late Wednesday that the euro's fall would
cut into its third-quarter earnings. Several analysts lowered their
earnings estimates for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 685.08 million
shares, compared to 697.96 million on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 4.09 to 538.09.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
