<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Holds on European Duties  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- To ease growing trade tensions with Europe,
President Clinton has decided to hold off -- for now -- slapping
heavy duties on a new set of luxury imports such as Scottish
cashmere sweaters, French mineral water, Italian cheese and British
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   New import duties on the goods are a way to retaliate against
the European Union's trade barriers to U.S. beef produced with
growth hormones and to bananas grown on American-run plantations in
the Caribbean and South America.
</P>
<P>
   But at a United Nations summit in New York last week, British
Prime Minister Tony Blair pleaded with Clinton to hold off
publishing the list of goods to be sanctioned. He was especially
concerned about tariffs on British cashmere. Blair argued that the
action would aggravate the already-strained trade relations between
the EU and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to make a decision,'' White House press secretary
Joe Lockhart said Thursday. ''We're in the process now of deciding
how we will continue to deal with what we believe is intransigence
on the side of the Europeans. A final decision on what items will
be sanctioned has not been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the administration targeted $191.4 million worth of
European exports ranging from French handbags to British bed linens
for punitive 100 percent tariffs in the banana case.
</P>
<P>
   In the beef case, the United States imposed 100 percent tariffs
on $116.8 million worth of European products ranging from Danish
ham to German chocolate and French mustard and Roquefort cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Those sanctions amount to a 100 percent tariff. Such a tariff
would mean that a bottle of mineral water that once cost $1 would
now cost $2, explained Brendan Daly, a spokesman for the U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky. He too stressed that the list
had not been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Tariffs have been placed on various European products before,
but the list is to change periodically -- a ploy to make it
unpredictable and exert even more pressure on Europe to open its
market to beef and bananas.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in deciding the list of products to be sanctioned also
gives the administration more time to resolve another sticky trade
issue: Tax breaks that the United States gives major American
exporters, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   American businesses are able to avoid billions of dollars in
taxes every year by sheltering some foreign sales in offshore shell
companies. Earlier this year, the World Trade Organization ruled
that this practice, allowed under U.S. tax law, violated
international trade agreements. The WTO said the EU could retaliate
against the United States by sanctioning U.S. goods if America
didn't comply by Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration reworked the tax law. The House
approved the change Wednesday. The Senate is expected to take up
the measure soon.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. trade representative site: http://www.ustr.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
