<HEADLINE> U.S. Forces Training in Philippines  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon said Thursday that 200 U.S.
special forces troops training in the Philippines will not be
involved in the Philippine government's confrontation with
kidnappers. Special Filipino troops might benefit from their
participation in the training, a U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine government officials have suggested they might be
planning an assault against a rebel group involved in kidnappings
in the southern Philippines. Muslim rebels holding 19 Filipino and
foreign hostages threatened Thursday to attack local cities if the
military launched an assault.
</P>
<P>
   The special forces training was planned more than a year ago and
is the third or fourth such exercise this year, said a Pentagon
spokesman, Rear Adm. Craig Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not being done to train the Philippine special
operations forces, although there is certainly side benefit of
that, of them being present and training along with our forces,''
Quigley said. A few dozen Filipino troops are involved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is primarily being done because of the climate and the
geography and the landscape that you find in the Philippines as a
very good training ground to provide the training for U.S. special
operations forces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Training has already begun and is expected to last about 45
days.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no knowledge of the government of the Philippines
intentions as to how they plan on resolving the hostage
situation,'' Quigley said, adding that U.S. officials hope all
hostages will be released immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Separatists Muslims recently releases several of their foreign
hostages in exchange for millions of dollars supplied by Libya, but
they angered Philippine government officials by kidnapping three
more people from a Malaysian diving resort on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
