<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Would Lift Ban on Judge Fees  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate bill would lift an 11-year-old ban on
federal judges supplementing their incomes with speaking fees, a
measure that has the backing of Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   After Rehnquist wrote a letter to Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.,
supporting the idea, language ending the prohibition was included
in a spending bill covering the judiciary and the departments of
Justice, Commerce and State. That measure passed the Senate
Appropriations Committee on July 18, but has yet to come to the
Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The provision would affect the 1,500 federal judges with
lifetime appointments, whom Rehnquist argued have salaries matched
by some first-year associates in law firms. Federal judges' annual
pay ranges from $181,400 for the chief justice to $141,300 for
district judges, and does not rise annually to match inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The disparity between the salaries of the judicial and legal
profession cannot continue indefinitely without compromising the
morale of the federal judiciary and eventually its quality,''
Rehnquist wrote in his April 27 letter to McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement on Thursday, Rehnquist said he has long
supported boosting judges' salaries, at least to stay even with
inflation. He said he wrote to McConnell after the senator's office
contacted him about legislation McConnell was planning that would
lift the ban on judges receiving such fees, called honoraria.
</P>
<P>
   ''I indicated that I would support Sen. McConnell's efforts
because easing the ban on honoraria would at least provide
assistance to some judges,'' Rehnquist said. ''I remain committed
to pay increases for federal judges.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the proposal is unclear. No such language exists in
the House version of the spending bill, and some key Democrats
expressed reservations about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's outrageous,'' said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., the top
Democrat on the House Appropriations Committee. ''It'll go
somewhere over my dead body. I don't believe in judges or members
of Congress going around the country giving speeches for money.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It erodes confidence in judges' independence, it fosters
conflicts of interest, and it invites cynicism about the courts,''
said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., the top Democrat on the Senate
Judiciary Committee. ''Even worse, there's no accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics outside of Congress also say the plan would invite
potential conflicts of interest for judges.
</P>
<P>
   ''Honoraria are fees for service,'' said Fred Werthheimer,
president of Democracy 21, a private group that favors the
tightening of campaign finance and ethics rules. ''Lifetime judges
with the general responsibility for enforcing the law should not be
working in the employ of outside private interests. There should be
only one master for a judge, and that is the general public and the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to McConnell, Rehnquist said he is ''confident''
that the Judicial Conference -- the administrative arm of the
federal courts -- ''would provide reasonable guidelines or
regulations on honoraria to minimize potential abuses or
appearances of impropriety.''
</P>
<P>
   In a May 2 letter to Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., who chairs the
Senate Appropriations subcommittee that wrote the spending bill,
McConnell said lifting the honoraria ban ''would help address the
expanding salary gap and allow the federal judiciary to determine
its own ethical standards for the receipt'' of the fees.
</P>
<P>
   A 1989 law banned federal judges, members of Congress and many
top executive branch officials from accepting speaking fees. Judges
can make up to $21,195 a year from other outside sources, such as
by teaching, and may also receive trips to some professional events
that are paid for.
</P>
<P>
   Congress controls judges' salaries, which by tradition only rise
when lawmakers raise their own pay. The raise automatically happens
every year unless Congress votes to block it.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress are expected to grant themselves a 2.7
percent raise that will take effect in January, the third raise in
the past four years. Before that, the last raise took effect in
January 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The pay increase is legally limited by a formula that links it
to inflation and to raises the president proposes for federal civil
servants.
</P>
<P>
   The move to end the prohibition on judges' honoraria was first
reported in Thursday's Washington Post.
------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 4690.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   To search text of bills: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
