<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Wants Patients' Rights Vote  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Complaining that 50,000 Americans encounter a
delay or denial of medical care every day, President Clinton
accused Republicans of abusing their power by preventing a Senate
vote to expand managed-care patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''Time is running out in Congress and there is no more important
piece of unfinished business,'' the president said Thursday at a
ceremony to increase election-year pressure on Republicans. The
White House served notice it would make a political issue out of
the bill if Republicans block it, as appears likely.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to believe that in this case the narrow special
interests will thwart the clear will of the Senate and the House,
but if that is the case the ultimate arbiter will be the ballot box
on Election Day,'' presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined at the podium on the south driveway of the
White House by 20 osteopaths and physicians, all dressed in long
white medical coats. An electronic counter, atop an ambulance with
flashing lights, ticked off the number of Americans who have had
their health care denied or delayed since the House passed the
bipartisan measure by Reps. Charles Norwood, R-Ga., and John
Dingell, D-Mich. -- one every 1.74 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton began to speak, the counter read 16,980,173. When
he finished, it had clicked up to 16,990,489.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the Norwood-Dingell bill last fall. Clinton
said there are enough votes to pass it in the Senate, but
Republicans are planning to filibuster any attempt to bring it up.
It takes a simple majority -- 51 votes -- to pass a bill in the
Senate but it requires a three-fifths margin -- 60 votes -- to stop a
filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sept. 18, the ambulance, painted with the slogan
''Pass the Patients' Bill of Rights,'' will travel to events in
Delaware, Michigan, Pennsylvania and other states where rallies
will be held to urge reluctant senators to pass the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nearly 50,000 Americans every day face a delay or denial of
care,'' the president said. ''Nearly 50,000. Every hour, more than
2,000 people fail to get the treatment they need.''
</P>
<P>
   The most contentious provision of the bill would give consumers
the right to sue HMOs for inadequate care. Senate Republicans say
the measure would increase health care costs and lead to a barrage
of lawsuits. Clinton said the increase would be less than $2 a
month and would be worth the cost.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Health Plans, representing more than
1,000 HMOs, took issue with Clinton. ''Supporters call this a new
bill but it continues to rely on predatory lawsuits, and this is a
significant stumbling block for enacting real patient protection,''
AAHP President Karen Ignagni. She said that if the Norwood-Dingell
bill is approved, the ambulance on the White House lawn ''will be
chased by a legion of trial lawyers in hot pursuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the bill deserves to come to a vote, but ''an abuse
of the filibuster system'' is preventing that.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to persuade the leadership of the Senate to let a
majority vote on this, and if a majority's for it, to pass it,''
Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 1708 </TRAILER>
