<HEADLINE> Pataki announces funding for Great Lakes projects  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Some $560,000 in state money is going to
schools, agencies and environmental groups for projects relating to
the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 10 proposals were funded, Gov. George Pataki
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Lakes projects were funded through the state's Great
Lakes Protection Fund for 2000-2001, created in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The State University's Oswego campus got the largest single
grant, $99,956 to research the degradation in confined disposal
facilities, the storage areas where polluted dredge has to be
deposited by law.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the other projects receiving funding:
</P>
<P>
   -SUNY Syracuse, $99,729, to develop a model to assess salmon and
trout production potential in Lake Ontario's tributaries.
</P>
<P>
   -SUNY Buffalo, $84,961 to help quantify contaminant trends in
fish and wildlife in Lake Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   -SUNY Brockport, $76,786 to study levels of toxins in fish and
wildlife in Lake Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   -SUNY Syracuse, $53,436 to evaluate effects of habitat
restoration on northern pike and muskellunge.
</P>
<P>
   -The Nature Conservancy, central and western New York chapters,
$50,000 to develop and disseminate biological information on water
in Lake Erie gorges and streams.
</P>
<P>
   -Oswego County Environmental Management Council, $45,858 to
research rare, endangered and threatened species and ecological
communities in shoreline wetlands of Lake Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   -New York Sea Grant, Cornell University/SUNY Buffalo, $17,530 to
teach educators about problems facing the Great Lakes and ways to
present the information to classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   -New York Sea Grant, Cornell University, Ithaca, $16,889 to
develop extension and outreach program about Lake Ontario
fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   -SUNY Brockport, $14,981 to update information about lake
levels, erosion and remediation.
</P>
</TEXT>
