<HEADLINE> White House Opposes Alaska Drilling  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration said Thursday
rising fuel prices do not justify new oil drilling in
environmentally sensitive parts of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has long opposed new exploration in
the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge in Alaska and in several other
protected areas, arguing that the potential for harm to the
environment far outweighs possible gains in oil production.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president, at his core, does not believe that the right
approach here is to start drilling in Alaska or in the protected
areas,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no consideration of that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The price of oil is near a 10-year high, affecting gasoline and
home heating oil prices as fall weather approaches. The Energy
Department predicts home heating oil will cost 30 percent more this
winter than it did last, and natural gas will cost 27 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has other options to try to lower oil prices,
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have a number of ways that we have promoted to
decrease our dependence on foreign oil,'' he said. ''Unfortunately,
most of those have been stymied by the Republican Congress. We
continue to work. You'll see in some areas where they've blocked
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, congressional Republicans accused the Clinton-Gore
administration of squandering U.S. influence with oil-producing
nations and standing helpless to protect consumers now.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's Democratic presidential campaign shot back that
Republican rival George W. Bush has no energy policy at all, other
than ''to let his friends in the oil industry drill our wilderness
areas,'' as spokesman Doug Hattaway put it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore proposes tax breaks to help consumers buy an upcoming
generation of fuel-efficient vehicles as well as incentives for
energy efficient homes and cleaner power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed allowing drilling in the coastal strip of the
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
