<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer Centers To Help Out Parents  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Deborah Pryce is a lawyer, former judge and a
member of Congress. Yet she felt helpless and ''almost frozen with
fear'' when forced to select the right treatment for her daughter's
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got so much conflicting information and conflicting advice
on the treatment to get and where to turn for help,'' she said.
''These are life-and-death decisions. When you're paralyzed with
fear and grief it's so difficult to know who to trust.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, families facing such decisions should have access
to better information now that 237 cancer centers and children's
hospitals have decided to work together, coordinating their
research and setting up a national childhood cancer database. The
cooperative effort was announced Thursday at a Capitol Hill news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''How we have worked, unfortunately, has in some ways been in
competition,'' said Dr. Gregory Reaman, executive director of the
Center for Cancer and Blood Disorders at the Children's National
Medical Center. ''To some extent we were working at
cross-purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We as pediatric oncologists have a single enemy and that is
the cancer our children develop,'' Reaman said as he and other
cancer experts joined Pryce to announce the merger of four networks
of research hospitals into the unified Children's Oncology Group.
</P>
<P>
   Having the experts in agreement about the best types of
treatment for the different stages and kinds of cancer should make
it easier for parents trying to become instant experts on the
disease and the latest research, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will greatly assist families at the time of diagnosis that
are faced with decisions,'' Reaman said. ''There will be single
recommendations for clinical trials, making sure that every child,
regardless of where they live, has access.''
</P>
<P>
   The merged group intends to create a more efficient system for
collecting information about pediatric cancer cases and about the
results of various treatments and research programs. That, in turn,
should step up the pace of research into childhood cancer, Reaman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger has been in place for a few months, but many details
remain to be worked out, said Dr. G. Denman Hammond, professor of
pediatrics at the University of Southern California-Keck School of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   After Pryce's daughter, Caroline Pryce Walker, was diagnosed
with neuroblastoma in 1998, the congresswoman found herself
confronting specialists who laid out a series of options but who
didn't agree on how best to combat the rare, aggressive form of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Pryce, R-Ohio, eventually got Caroline into a program at a New
York hospital that allowed treatments to be administered from a
hospital close to home in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline died Sept. 4, 1999. She was 9 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Childhood Cancer Foundation site:
http://www.nccf.org
</P>
<P>
   Childhood Cancer Month site: http://www.ChildhoodCancerMonth.org
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pryce's site: http://www.house.gov/pryce
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
