<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCall critical of oversight of welfare programs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - State comptroller H. Carl McCall on Thursday
accused New York labor officials of doing a poor job monitoring
local welfare employment and training programs.
</P>
<P>
   McCall made the charge as he released an audit that found the
state Department of Labor was not making sure local agencies were
performing necessary case work such as assessing recipients' skills
and providing employment plans.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors examined 200 case files from New York City and Broome,
Jefferson, Niagara, Steuben and Ulster counties. Among their
findings: employability assessments were not done 20 percent of the
time; there was no record of an evaluation of the recipient's
literacy or English language skills 39 percent of the time; 30
percent of the case files had no employment plans; there was no
record that recipients were asked about previous job experiences 21
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said that state and local officials are accountable for
providing the tools necessary for able bodied recipients to get
work and that ''the state Department of Labor is not living up to
its responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   State labor officials responded that incomplete records do not
necessarily mean the work was not being done. State labor
department spokeswoman Betsy McCormack noted that New York state
has reduced its welfare rolls by 848,000 recipients since 1995,
surpassing federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know we're doing a good job,'' McCormack said. ''Success
speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall released a second audit that found serious flaws in the
way state labor officials keep track of recipients' work hours. A
new Welfare to Work Caseload Management System promised since 1993
is now scheduled to be operational next spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
