<HEADLINE> Alleged Central Park victims ask for information to help lawsuits  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Eight women who say they were sexually abused in
the aftermath of the Puerto Rican Day Parade asked a judge Thursday
to order the city to give them materials that will help them
prepare lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The eight women are among the 50-plus who charged that after the
parade on June 11, young men doused them with water, stripped them,
and groped their buttocks and breasts while police refused to act
on their complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Karten, a lawyer for two of the women, said they want
police surveillance and amateur videotapes; assignment rosters,
especially for areas where the women were molested; and 911 and
radio transmission audio tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The court petition became necessary, Karten said, after city
lawyers refused to let the women's lawyers examine material they
eventually would get anyway after they file the suits against the
city and the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the city, Assistant Corporation Counsel Susan
Pondich, told State Supreme Court Justice Marcy S. Friedman that
she did not believe the women were entitled to anything before the
lawsuits were filed.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Rubenstein, a lawyer for two other women, said, ''We
think it's unconscionable that the city is fighting us every step
of the way. Our clients cooperated with Internal Affairs, they
should cooperate with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman reserved decision on whether she would order the city
to turn over the materials. In June, she issued a temporary
restraining order barring the city from destroying the material the
women have asked for.
</P>
<P>
   Karten said lawyers hoped they would see some material from the
Police Department's Internal Affairs Bureau (IAB) investigation of
alleged police inaction, ''but the whole investigation by IAB has
been a whitewash.''
</P>
<P>
   ''For all intents and purposes the investigation's been
shelved,'' said Karten. ''Why are they afraid to give over
information about people who did something wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department has accused only one cop of failing to do
his job, Karten said, even though the female complainants alleged
that 20 to 30 officers had ignored them when they asked for help.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Antenen, spokesman for the Police Department, denied that
the department was being obstructionist. ''It's a matter that under
litigation,'' he said. ''There's a process for this, and it's
underway.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Thompson, spokeswoman for the Manhattan district
attorney's office, said one juvenile and 29 adults have been
charged with sex abuse, riot and robbery in connection with the
park attacks. She said 17 have been indicted, and the adult
defendants' ages range from 16 to 40.
</P>
</TEXT>
