<DOCNO> APW20000914.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Probe: No Undue Influence on Army  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An investigation by three Republican-led
Senate committees found the Clinton administration has not exerted
undue influence over Army Corps of Engineers construction
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But it also deemed as unnecessary a Pentagon effort, now on
hold, to give administration officials more say over which projects
the corps pursues.
</P>
<P>
   ''After a careful evaluation of the material, we did not find
evidence of illegality, or of inappropriate political influence on
the corps' professional judgments,'' Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., said
Thursday. ''Similarly, the material provided to the committee does
not establish the need for any significant civil works management
reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's Environment and Public Works Committee, along with the
Appropriations and Armed Services committees, began the
investigation in April after Army Secretary Louis Caldera proposed
management changes intended to increase accountability at the
corps.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, long the target of environmental and taxpayer
groups, is the subject of several ongoing investigations into
allegations that top military officials rigged a case for spending
$1 billion on agribusiness-backed lock expansions on the
Mississippi and Illinois rivers.
</P>
<P>
   In his proposal, Caldera asserted that the Army's assistant
secretary for civil works was responsible for all final decisions
on projects in the corps' $4 billion flood control and river
construction portfolio. He was aiming to ensure the corps answered
to the administration instead of to its traditional allies on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The committee chairmen said Caldera's changes might allow the
Clinton administration to tamper with corps' project
recommendations to Congress for political reasons, and Caldera
withdrew his plan.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent Thursday to Defense Secretary William Cohen,
the chairmen said that, based on reams of documents supplied by the
corps, they view Caldera's changes as unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   They wrote that any changes should be deferred at least until
President Clinton's nominee to be the new military commander of the
corps, Maj. Gen. Robert Flowers, is confirmed and has a chance to
settle into his post.
</P>
<P>
   An Army spokeswoman did not immediately return a call for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance before the Senate Environment panel Thursday,
Flowers said it is clear that he answers to civilian leaders at the
Army and the administration. Also during that hearing, senators
from both parties described in forceful terms their concerns about
problems at the corps.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been legitimate policy issues raised on topics like
the integrity of corps economic analyses and the future role of the
corps,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers pledged to give full attention to ''maintaining the
integrity of the Corps of Engineers.''
</P>
<P>
   He also appeared receptive to a few changes long sought by
environmental groups, including a ban on projects that cause
environmental damage too costly to fix and the inclusion of those
expenses in project analyses.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives from the conservation community were
disappointed that proposals to reform the way corps projects are
reviewed and approved did not get a stronger endorsement from
Flowers or from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''Reform is needed to bring this out-of-control agency back in
line,'' said David Conrad, water resources specialist at the
National Wildlife Federation. ''The foxes are literally designing
the chicken coop.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Army Corps of Engineers:
http://www.mvr.usace.army.mil/pdw/nav--study.htm
</P>
<P>
   American Rivers: http://www.americanrivers.org
</P>
</TEXT>
