<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: State fails to follow Megan's Law when sex offenders released </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The release of a convicted rapist before
prosecutors could be told was not an accident but an example of the
state's systematic failure to keep track of sex offenders who leave
prison, according to a state Senate investigation.
</P>
<P>
   County prosecutors are routinely notified just as sex offenders
are walking out of state prisons before any Megan's Law
notifications can begin, former U.S. Attorney Michael Chertoff told
a Senate committee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The inmate is out the door, and the county is only able to
find out the address is phony after he's released,'' Chertoff said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary committee hired Chertoff after the
Corrections Department admitted it made numerous errors before
convicted rapist Raymond Alves was released in March.
</P>
<P>
   Now the committee will ask corrections Commissioner Jack Terhune
how long the state knew sex offenders routinely left prison with no
way for prosecutors to comply with Megan's Law, chairman Sen. Bill
Gormley, R-Atlantic, said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no system. It is disjointed if not dysfunctional,''
Gormley said.
</P>
<P>
   Terhune admitted Thursday that sex offenders were released
before authorities could be notified. But he said that since the
Alves case, new safeguards are in place.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some facilities were 100 percent compliant. Some were not.
We've changed that,'' Terhune said.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner, who has not seen Chertoff's report, said the
committee should look at what has happened since he ordered a
central processing system for sex offenders. Other safeguards
include multiple reviews of release dates and possible new computer
systems, Terhune said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had to put some procedures in place and we've done that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alves had served less than half of a 47-year sentence for the
rape of a teen in Fair Lawn and the assault of a Clifton teen.
Prosecutors in Bergen and Passaic counties said they would have
tried to block the release had they been alerted, as state law
requires.
</P>
<P>
   Once freed, Alves took off on a 12-day cross-country bus trip
before he was arrested and charged with violating sections of
Megan's Law.
</P>
<P>
   The sex offender notification rules require convicts to provide
a valid address and to register with local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   But New Jersey's prison system offers no single way to comply
with Megan's Law, Chertoff said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Alves episode was not a one-time accident or a problem,
but a symptom of a statewide failure of notification,'' Chertoff
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that's symptomatic of the fact that what we're dealing
with is not failure at one particular institution,'' Chertoff said.
''It really is a widespread failure in the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the attorney general's office, county prosecutors
detailed when and how often they were notified of prisoners'
releases. Chertoff compiled 15 months worth of figures, ending in
March.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires notification 90 days before a scheduled
release.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen and Essex counties reported being notified seven days
before or after an inmate's release, nearly as many times as they
were told before the 90-day requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Several counties maintain their own tracking system, and some
claim they are not notified before any release, Chertoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Chertoff said he found no single form or no uniform reporting
procedure for the individual state prisons to communicate with the
21 county prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ''What strikes me is in the age of computers, you would think
all this would be online,'' Chertoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley said the task now is to determine what the Corrections
Department is doing to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of dwelling on everything that might have been
wrong,'' Gormley said, ''we'll come up with a system that's right
and works.''
</P>
<P>
   Chertoff said he requested documents from Terhune's office,
including some reports of a February meeting at which the
deficiencies were discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Those reports were not provided before Thursday's hearing, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The state indicated it would reply sometime this week, Gormley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Terhune would be asked to address the charges raised by Chertoff
at the next committee meeting, Gormley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have been there today if I had been asked to,''
Terhune said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
