<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 95; Nasdaq Gains 20  </HEADLINE>
By LISA SINGHANIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chips fell sharply Thursday on
profit-taking and concerns about the drop in the euro currency, but
technology stocks moved higher for a second straight session on
upbeat speculation about corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 94.71 at 11,087.47.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index rose
19.97 to 3,913.86 but the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 4.04 to
1,480.87.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second day of a small tech-stock rally, which began
Wednesday with a 44-point gain in the Nasdaq. The index rose nearly
100 points during Thursday's trading, but couldn't hold the gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''We rallied in the morning, but the market just didn't have any
sustainability,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, an analyst with
Prudential Securities. ''The trend here in September is that there
is no trend. September has historically been a very rough month,
and it is this year, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Software maker Oracle traded up $3.13 at $84.94 on investor
anticipation of its quarterly earnings report and an upgrade to
''strong buy'' from ''outperform'' by a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
analyst. Oracle's earnings, released after the market closed, beat
Wall Street expectations by 4 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks also got a boost from Conexant Systems, which
rose $15.56 to $52.63, a nearly 42 percent increase. The company
announced late Wednesday it was spinning its Internet
infrastructure business off into a separate company.
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase rose $2.13 to $106.94, ending a slide that started
at the beginning of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems spent most of the day up, but closed down 6 cents
at $61.25. Intel also briefly rallied before falling $1.63 to
$59.63.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nasdaq is playing a little catch-up because they had a
serious setback of underperfomance as we got into September,'' said
Ronald J. Hill, an investment strategist and partner at Brown
Brothers Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, blue chips slumped on worries that a drop in the
euro, Europe's currency, will hurt corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest U.S. companies are scheduled to report earnings in
the next four weeks. Investor uncertainty about how strong those
profits will be has left many unwilling to make large commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Colgate-Palmolive fell $8.81 to $47.38, a 15 percent drop, after
a Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown analyst downgraded the stock, citing
the influence of the weak euro and higher fuel costs. Later in the
day, the company issued a statement saying it was comfortable with
third-quarter earnings estimates, but offered no other specifics.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's also fell, declining $1.06 to $26.94, after it warned
late Wednesday that the euro's fall would hurt its bottom line.
Several analysts lowered their earnings estimates for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, Wall Street got a lift from the Labor
Department's report that wholesale prices fell an unexpected 0.2
percent last month, the first drop in four months. The decline
followed a flat reading in the Producer Price Index in July.
</P>
<P>
   The report was further evidence that the economy is slowing and
reassured investors that the inflation-wary Fed is unlikely to
raise rates for a seventh time since June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had some good data today for the soft-landing scenario, but
obviously there is still not enough confidence overall to get
things totally on track,'' said Hill, the analyst with Brown
Brothers Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange. Consolidated volume came to 1.21 billion
shares, less than the 1.29 billion shares Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 5.21 to 539.21.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average was up 0.14 percent.
Germany's DAX index rose 0.60 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up
1.19 percent, and France's CAC-40 rose 1.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
