<HEADLINE> Former security guard pleads guilty to cover-up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - A former Trump Plaza Hotel &AMP; Casino
guard who covered up the beating death of a rowdy gambler has
pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Waldron, 51, of Egg Harbor Township, who was originally
charged with witness tampering, pleaded guilty to providing a
fictitious report on Monday. She was sentenced to one year of
probation.
</P>
<P>
   The case stemmed from the Sept. 8, 1998, death of Hue Q. To, 25,
of Plainfield, who was ejected from the casino for panhandling,
trying to steal chips from other gamblers and threatening to kill
guards.
</P>
<P>
   To died of a spinal injury after a scuffle in a Trump Plaza
security office. Another former guard, Mark Petty, 37, of Galloway
Township, was convicted last month of second-degree manslaughter in
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Waldron allegedly threatened four guards, warning them not to
tell the truth about what happened because it would send Petty to
jail and result in their firings.
</P>
<P>
   Waldron, who lost her job as a result of the incident and now
drives a bus, pleaded guilty rather than go to trial. She admitted
making false statements in reports to the state Division of Gaming
Enforcement about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we were confident with respect to a trial, whenever
there's a jury, there's always a degree of uncertainty and there's
always a risk,'' said Peter Bruso, her lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Petty is to be sentenced Sept. 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
