<HEADLINE> Man charged with strangling 18-year-old census enumerator  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) - A Piscataway man has been charged with
strangling an 18-year-old man who worked for two weeks as a U.S.
Census Bureau worker in Newark, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Cory Stewart's mother reported him missing on May 31, three days
after he disappeared from his Newark home, authorities said. His
body was found in June in a drainage ditch in Piscataway, but was
not positively identified until Wednesday, investigators told the
Home News and Tribune of East Brunswick in Thursday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Rashid A. Peterson-Gaines was arrested Monday in the parking lot
of Piscataway's municipal court and charged with Stewart's slaying,
authorities said. He had gone to court for a hearing on minor
traffic violations and had showed up on the wrong day, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's girlfriend had told authorities that she saw the two
men together in Newark sometime before May 26, Middlesex County
Prosecutor Glenn Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart worked for the U.S. Census Bureau as an enumerator in
his neighborhood for two weeks in May, said Ligia Jaquez, assistant
regional census manager at the Census' regional center in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart wanted to save money to buy clothes for his senior prom,
Jaquez said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a good worker for us. Good kid,'' Jaquez said.
</P>
<P>
   Jaquez said Stewart's crew leader last heard from him on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson-Gaines entered a not guilty plea to murder Thursday and
was held on $300,000 bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
