<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court: Nigerian human rights abuses can be heard in U.S. court </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A lawsuit charging that the Royal Dutch
Petroleum Co. assisted in the torture and murder of Nigerian
activists can be heard in federal court in New York rather than
England, an appeals court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan ruling by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
was praised by lawyers for four plaintiffs, including one who now
lives in the United States, two others living in Canada and a woman
living in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   A message left with lawyers for the defendants, Royal Dutch
Petroleum Co., incorporated in the Netherlands, and Shell Transport
and Trading Co., incorporated in Great Britain, was not immediately
returned.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies jointly control and operate the Royal
Dutch/Shell Group, a vast international network of affiliated but
formally independent oil and gas companies, according to the ruling
written by Judge Pierre N. Leval.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs alleged in a lawsuit in federal court in
Manhattan that one of the affiliated companies, Shell Petroleum
Development Co. of Nigeria Limited, coercively took land for oil
development without adequate compensation and polluted air and
water in the Ogoni region of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   They said Shell Nigeria recruited the Nigerian police and
military to attack local villages and suppress the organized
opposition to its development projects.
</P>
<P>
   One plaintiff sued on behalf of his father and another on behalf
of her husband after both men were hanged, along with Ogoni
leaders, in 1995 after being convicted of murder by a special
military tribunal on charges that the lawsuit alleged were based on
fabricated evidence. Another plaintiff alleged he was illegally
detained by Nigerian authorities while a fourth said she was beaten
and shot by the Nigerian military in a raid on her village.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Brown Chomsky, the lead lawyer for the plaintiffs, called
the ruling a ''significant victory.''
</P>
<P>
   It reversed a decision by U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood in
Manhattan that concluded the case should be tried in England.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court found that Wood failed to properly consider
the importance of letting a U.S. resident choose where the trial
occurs and the interests of the United States in litigating claims
of violations of international standards of human rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court praised British courts but said the defendants
had failed to prove that ''pertinent factors tilt sufficiently
strongly in favor of trial in the foreign forum.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the 2nd Circuit said the companies should be
subject to a U.S.-based trial because they maintain an Investor
Relations Office in New York City at an annual cost of more than a
half-million dollars per year.
</P>
<P>
   Chomsky said the ruling means that multinational corporations
who gain money from trading in U.S. markets ''won't be able to
pretend that they're not here.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Corporations can be held liable when they join forces with
authoritarian dictatorships that abuse their own population,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer M. Green, another lawyer who worked on the case, said
the ruling will mean corporations ''can't do business here and then
evade accountability for human rights violations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-14-00 1853 </TRAILER>
