<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Committee OKs Hawaiian Bill  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A controversial measure granting federal
recognition to Native Hawaiians was approved by a Senate committee
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the right thing to do,'' said Sen. Daniel Inouye,
Hawaii's Democratic senator and vice chairman of the Indian Affairs
Committee, which passed the measure by a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation sponsored by Sen. Daniel Akaka will affect the
state's 200,000 Native Hawaiians and essentially define the
political status of those descended from the islands' original
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   It suggests Congress create a framework for recognizing a
''government-to-government'' relationship with a Native Hawaiian
governing body similar to the relationships enjoyed by 556
federally recognized American Indian and Alaska Native tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's vote follows a week of raucous hearings in Hawaii
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Some Native Hawaiians who oppose the measure say it gives the
federal government too much of a role in the Hawaiian sovereignty
process. Many of those critics also advocate Hawaii's secession
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also faces an uphill battle in Congress. Sen. Pete
Domenici, R-N.M., said Thursday he still has concerns about how the
bill would affect Indian programs. ''I clearly would not like to
bring a very large number of new people within the gamut of Indian
Affairs,'' Domenici said at the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters tried to assure him the Native Hawaiians would not
become a part of Indian programs. ''This bill does not make them an
Indian tribe. All this bill does is begin the process of the
government recognizing Native Hawaiians,'' said Inouye.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Rep. Patsy Mink, a member of Hawaii's all Democratic
delegation, has so far declined to sign on as a cosponsor of the
House version sponsored by Rep. Neil Abercrombie, also of Hawaii.
She has suggested the bill be changed to include a referendum among
Hawaiians on what form of self-governance they want before pursing
federal recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the bill's struggle is Congress' plans to adjourn in
the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The bills were offered after the U.S. Supreme Court's Feb. 23
ruling striking down the state's Hawaiians-only restriction for
voting in Office of Hawaiian Affairs elections as unconstitutional
racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiian leaders fear that ruling could be the basis for future
court rulings dismantling more than 180 federal and state programs
benefitting Hawaiians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 1856 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000914.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge 'greatly disappointed' in destruction of documents  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - A federal judge said Thursday he is ''greatly
disappointed'' in the U.S. Treasury Department for destroying
documents sought by victims of a terrorist bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge, Royce C. Lamberth of U.S. District Court,
declined to impose sanctions on the government, saying he believes
the documents were destroyed accidentally.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came in the case of Stephen Flatow of West Orange,
N.J., whose daughter Alisa was killed in a 1995 bombing in the Gaza
Strip. Flatow sued Iran under a 1996 anti-terrorism law that
authorized legal action against state sponsors of terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth ruled in Flatow's favor and ordered Iran to pay $247.5
million in damages. More than two years have passed, however, and
Flatow has not collected a cent. The U.S. government has opposed
his efforts to collect the judgment by laying claim to frozen
Iranian assets.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest court action, Flatow asked Lamberth to compel the
Treasury Department to produce documents on Iranian assets, as
demanded in a June 5, 1998, subpoena. The Treasury Department
objected to the subpoena as ''unduly burdensome and overly broad.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Lamberth limited the scope of the subpoena but
granted Flatow's motion to compel production of relevant documents.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also wrote that Flatow ''correctly asserts that the
Treasury Department has recently destroyed many documents covered
by the subpoena.''
</P>
<P>
   But he found that the destruction occurred ''in coordination
with an office renovation project, making it unlikely that an
underhanded scheme was afoot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
