<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schools closed again in Hamilton Township  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAMILTON, N.J. (AP) - Striking teachers and school district
employees in Hamilton Township were not expected to receive
paychecks Friday.
</P>
<P>
   School board lawyer Dennis DeSantis said in a letter to the
Hamilton Township Education Association and the Hamilton Township
School Secretaries Association that striking employees are not due
any money.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be no direct deposit or checks distributed to your
affected members on Friday, September 15,'' DeSantis wrote.
''Payroll will be adjusted and checks will be distributed to
reflect earnings due minus deductions following the job action.''
</P>
<P>
   DeSantis did not return phone calls and messages Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Joseph, spokeswoman for the New Jersey Education
Association, said teachers and other school employees should get
paychecks for days they worked preparing for the start of classes
on Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said teachers worked Sept. 5 while the custodial staff,
food service workers and secretaries worked for several days or
even weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real point is that they are due some money,'' Joseph said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for the teachers and the Hamilton Township school
board were expected to meet at 6 p.m. Thursday for the fifth
consecutive night of contract talks. The teachers union was not
expected to hold a general membership meeting early Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Striking teachers and school officials remained at odds over
salary issues Thursday, but some progress was reported in contract
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said talks ended early Thursday morning without a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was some movement on some other issues, but not on
salary,'' Joseph said.
</P>
<P>
   Classes were canceled again Thursday, the seventh day schools
have been closed since the strike began last week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 1,100 teachers are defying a back-to-work order
issued last week by Superior Court Judge Anthony J. Parrillo. The
judge has ordered $300 fines to teachers for every day of missed
work. The union must pay a $100,000-a-day fine.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 400 school secretaries, electricians, plumbers and other
skilled workers, who have a valid contract but are supporting the
strike, must pay a $50-a-day fine.
</P>
<P>
   School board officials have said fines would be deducted from
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers union lawyer Arnold Mellk said the district can not
collect the fines from the union or the teachers until the court
holds a hearing on whether they are financially able to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Parrillo has yet to schedule another hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The Times of Trenton reported in Thursday's editions that
DeSantis' wife - a teacher and member of the striking association
recovering at home from recent surgery - would not be fined.
</P>
<P>
   DeSantis told the Times that employees who have a ''legitimate
reason'' for not being at school as well as those who crossed the
picket lines to return to work would be exempt from paying the
fines.
</P>
</TEXT>
