<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmaker hopes bill would allow towns to ban smoking  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A state senator from Mercer County claims a
new bill will close a loophole she says allowed a judge to dismiss
Princeton's attempt to severely limit smoking in public.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Shirley Turner, D-Mercer, introduced a bill Thursday to
provide legal protection to towns that propose anti-smoking
measures.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would give authority to municipalities, local health
commissions and other boards to adopt such ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   ''Individual communities should have the authority to protect
public health through the establishment of smoking bans,'' Turner
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's bill also allows ordinances to apply to small
businesses, retail and food stores and bars.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill can provide sound legal protection for towns seeking
to crack down on smoking,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Princeton Regional Health Commission passed its ban in
June, it appeared to be the strictest anti-smoking ordinance in the
state, prohibiting lighting up in bars, restaurants and workplaces.
It restricted smoking to homes, cigar shops or outdoors. Violators
faced fines from $100 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia-based National Smokers Alliance and three Princeton
bars and restaurants filed a lawsuit challenging the ban June 8.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Linda R. Feinberg sided with them on Aug.
29.
</P>
<P>
   In the 64-page ruling, Feinberg agreed with the alliance's
arguments that the health commission did not have the authority to
enact the ban for fire-safety purposes. The judge also held that
the ordinance is pre-empted by state law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
