<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers walk out again in Buffalo strike  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Striking Buffalo teachers said they would
be back in class Friday after an angry Supreme Court judge ordered
an end to the walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Teachers Federation President Philip Rumore said
teachers would honor a request by a state mediator to return to
class for at least the next three school days while contract
negotiations continue.
</P>
<P>
   Rumore and other union executives got a legal break Thursday
when Justice Kevin Dillon threw out contempt charges against them
on a technicality. New charges, however, are likely because the
strike violates the state's Taylor Law and a temporary restraining
order signed by Dillon at the district's request.
</P>
<P>
   After suspending their strike all week, the BTF's 3,700 teachers
unexpectedly resumed the walkout at 7:05 a.m. Thursday, stranding
thousands of schoolchildren at bus stops and on schoolbuses.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Marion Canedo canceled classes in the district of
47,000 and the city opened emergency shelters for children. Bus
drivers ran their routes to tell parents of the closing. Children
left unattended were picked up and cared for until parents could be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the city, as teachers picketed, children wearing
backpacks walked along streets, with and without adults.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the absolute life of me, I cannot comprehend any reason
whatsoever why someone would conclude that harm from the actions of
this morning would fall on anyone other than the children of the
city of Buffalo,'' Dillon said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is about the greedy self-interest of the executive
committee of the Buffalo Teachers Federation who have no interest
in protecting the health, safety and welfare of our children,''
said Board of Education President Paul Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Rumore led teachers in a noontime rally on the steps of City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The union claims the district has not bargained in good faith to
replace a contract that expired in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''The district reneged and actually decreased the offers that
the superintendent and chief negotiator agreed upon previously,''
the union said in a prepared statement. ''It is apparent that the
superintendent and chief negotiator do not have the authority to
negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said the district's latest offer Wednesday contained
raises of 16.5 percent over four years. The union, he said, is
seeking 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In court Thursday, Dillon gave the teachers a pass for their
walkout last Thursday, dismissing contempt charges filed against
union leaders. He agreed with BTF lawyers who argued that paperwork
related to a court order forbidding the strike had been improperly
filed.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, however, solidified a temporary restraining order
issued Tuesday ordering teachers back to work.
</P>
<P>
   BTF attorney Michael Sawicki said he expected the city to file
new contempt charges stemming from the latest walkout.
</P>
<P>
   After reporting for the first day of school last Wednesday,
teachers went on strike an hour before classes began the following
day. With word of progress in contract talks, the teachers
suspended their strike and had reported to work every day since.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't like it,'' said Alisha Bly, 10, of Buffalo as she
walked home with her three siblings and her father. ''I think the
teachers should get what they want instead of the board cheating
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Stephany, the mother of a fifth-grader, said the strike has
interfered with her search for a new job.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's so nerve-racking, not knowing if there's going to be
school or not,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her 10-year-old son, Steven Smodics, took advantage of
the free time to meet U.S. Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton,
who was making a campaign stop in their Buffalo neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, who was endorsed by the Buffalo teachers union,
condemned the walkout.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really believe strongly that we do have to give more support
to our teachers, both in terms of financial support, but also
respect and authority and discipline, the things that make our
schools successful,'' Clinton said. ''But there has to be a
recognition that the most important obligation is to be in that
classroom teaching our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Picketing teachers said they would stand together.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd all rather be in the classroom. But we also want to get
what we deserve and what the kids deserve,'' said special education
teacher Ros Gottstein said as she picketed outside South Park High
School.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
