<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Case To Tackle Violence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three days after a federal report said the
entertainment industry aggressively markets violent, adult-rated
products to young people, President Clinton pushed the industry to
get more involved in tackling youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   The president's words were echoed by America Online Chairman
Steve Case at a luncheon Thursday hosted by the National Campaign
Against Youth Violence, established at a White House summit in 1999
by U.S. business and political leaders. Case, who serves on the
campaign committee, pledged to do more considering his company's
proposed merger with entertainment giant Time-Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the FTC's report reminded us this week, we have a lot more
work to do, especially those of us in the media and
communications-entertainment industries,'' Case said. ''I'm
certainly looking forward to working with other leaders in what
will soon be my new industry: to take a fresh look at what's being
done and to make a commitment to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that would include re-evaluating marketing practices to
restrict children's access to violent and content inappropriate for
young people as well as helping to give parents the tools they need
to determine what movies and music and World Wide Web sites their
kids should or shouldn't be seeing.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC report said that even movies rated R, which require an
adult to accompany children under 17, and video games that carry an
M rating for 17 and over are routinely marketed toward younger
people.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton highlighted some progress in the campaign against youth
violence: content rating systems for television and video games,
parental controls for the Internet and V-chips that let parents
control what their children watch on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it is unrealistic to expect that we can get where we need
to go if the major entertainment media are not involved,'' Clinton
said. ''They have to buy onto this. And they have to understand
that in the end, the most successful companies have a big interest
in living in a safe society, and a good society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
