<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs 2 More Spending Bills  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans ignored a White House veto threat
and muscled two spending bills through the House on Thursday, even
as their election-season drive to use 90 percent of next year's
surplus for debt reduction put Democrats momentarily on the
defensive.
</P>
<P>
   With the Oct. 1 start of fiscal 2001 drawing ever closer, the
House approved a $414 million measure financing the District of
Columbia's government. The vote was 217-207.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, they voted 212-209 for a second bill
providing $30.3 billion for Congress' own operations, the Treasury
Department and smaller agencies. The measure would also phase out
the 3 percent federal excise tax on telephone service over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Both votes were nearly party-line, with Republicans saying they
had failed to work out compromises with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're on the move here,'' said House Appropriations Committee
Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But with 11 of the 13 annual spending bills for the coming
fiscal year still incomplete -- including eight that face Clinton
administration veto threats -- Congress has a long way to go before
lawmakers can go home for the presidential and congressional
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complained about both measures the House approved
Thursday, though only the Treasury-legislative measure faced a veto
threat by President Clinton. They complained about shortfalls for
student aid and an environmental cleanup in the District of
Columbia, and cuts in Clinton requests for the Internal Revenue
Service and counterterrorism programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''In essence, this dog has three tails and no legs,'' Rep. David
Obey, D-Wis., said of the measure for the Treasury, Congress and
the telephone tax. ''It isn't going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the House Ways and Means Committee voted 33-0 to
create a process for using all but about $27 billion of next year's
projected $268 billion projected budget surplus for reducing the
national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure, all of the Social Security and Medicare
surpluses -- plus most of the rest of next year's budget surplus --
would be directed to debt reduction. It would take 60 votes in the
100-member Senate to do otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The bill reflected the GOP's newest goal: reserving 90 percent
of next year's projected federal surplus to reduce the national
debt. Unable to force their biggest tax cuts into law over Clinton
vetoes, Republicans hope their new drive will help them grab credit
for debt reduction, which is popular with the public, and limit
Clinton's efforts to use the money to boost spending.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't allow the president to squander the surplus on big
government spending,'' House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they scoffed at the measure, all of the Ways and Means
Committee's Democrats who were present voted for the bill,
underlining the political appeal of debt reduction. And they said
they would do the same thing next week in the full House.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all going to vote for this thing because it's like a lot
of nice-sounding press releases, a nice thing to say,'' said Rep.
Robert Matsui, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats insisted that when it came to making actual
decisions about taxes and spending, the $27 billion the GOP would
use for spending and tax cuts would not be enough, even for
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   They cited both parties' desires to cut taxes for telephone
users, students, inner cities and some small businesses and to
boost spending for schools, hospitals and nursing homes, fighting
forest fires, defense and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also argued that the new GOP goal was an abrupt
abandonment of the Republicans' push for big tax cuts, and of GOP
presidential candidate George W. Bush's call for a 10-year, $1.3
trillion tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now, with their 90-10 debt reduction plan, Republicans have
essentially repudiated their own agenda, which they have pursued
vigorously for the last six years,'' said House Minority Leader
Dick Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Klain, adviser to Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
presidential candidate, said the GOP debt-reduction plan meant that
''Republicans effectively declared their nominee's budget dead on
arrival even before it's clear whether he'll be given an
opportunity to submit a budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said the congressional GOP's plan
is ''very understandable'' because given Clinton's tax-bill vetoes,
it was needed to keep Clinton from a ''spending spree.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as House Democrats ridiculed the GOP debt-reduction
plan, they cited it as a reason to oppose the elimination of the
telephone tax right now. They said that if only 10 percent of the
surplus is to be used for spending and tax cuts, all tax-cutting
ideas should be considered before even a popular one like the
telephone tax is enacted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 1923 </TRAILER>
