<HEADLINE> High-tech firms show their wares  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SOUTHINGTON, Conn. (AP) - Innovations in fields ranging from
solar power to pharmaceuticals went on display Thursday as
Connecticut's high-tech companies got together for technology
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering of 45 firms was designed to help companies
publicize their products, expose them to potential investors, and
perhaps find other firms who sell complementary products and
services.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's great networking,'' said Andrew Marsh, president of
newly-formed Solar Dynamics in Avon. The company sells solar power
cells in isolated areas not wired for electricity.
</P>
<P>
   For Eric Stobin, a sales representative from Wilton-based
Spinergy Inc., it was a chance to meet people in other fields than
his own. His company makes lightweight, high-performance wheels for
high-end bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's nice to partner up with companies that are outside the
industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 800 visitors strolled past booths bathed in subdued
lighting on posh carpets at the upscale Aqua Turf Club, some
looking for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Dowd, manager for process at CiDRA Corp., which makes
fiber-optic components, said his company started with one employee
in 1996 and now employes 256 people.
</P>
<P>
   ''We probably need another 200 by next summer,'' Dowd said,
moments after snagging a resume from a visitor at his booth.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Innovations sponsored the exhibition. The Rocky Hill
organization received state funding in 1989 to invest in
Connecticut's budding technology firms and share in the profits.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Brandyberry, the group's executive vice president, said
the investments have paid off. The organization has been
self-sustaining for five years, and invested a record $31 million
in emerging Connecticut high-tech companies last year.
</P>
<P>
   The companies that have received investment capital from
Connecticut Innovations now employ 2,100 and generate more than
$315 milllion yearly in sales, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a vibrant technology economy in Connecticut,'' said
Brandyberry.
</P>
</TEXT>
