<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Immigration judge: Ex-Marine can stay in the country because of war record </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - An immigrant from the Dominican Republic who
fought in Vietnam, but faced deportation because of a drug
conviction should be allowed to stay in America because of his war
record, an immigration judge has ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Victoria Ghartey signed the ruling in Manhattan Monday,
terminating deportation proceedings against Luis Perez-Portes, a
54-year-old Queens resident.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't think of an individual more American, more proud of
his country, than Mr. Perez-Portes,'' said his lawyer, Ismael
Gonzalez. ''He was overjoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling clears the way for Perez-Portes to pursue his
application to become a citizen of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A message left with the Immigration and Naturalization Service
office seeking comment was not immediately returned. Gonzalez,
however, said he had been told that the INS planned to appeal the
case to the Board of Immigration Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Perez-Portes was convicted May 24, 1996 in U.S. District Court
in West Virginia for possession with intent to distribute cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced to two years in prison for the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Perez-Portes came to the United States at age 9, and joined the
U.S. Marine Corps in 1964 after completing the 10th grade. He was
sent to Vietnam, where he served for almost two years. While there
he was decorated and promoted to corporal. He was honorably
discharged and settled back in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the Marines, he worked as a laborer and farmer in
New York, Pennsylvania and West Virginia, and raised four children
with his wife, a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said Perez-Portes is eligible to remain in the United
States because of a provision of federal law allowing citizenship
for an alien who has served honorably at any time in the armed
forces for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The judge concluded that the provision could act as an exception
to good moral character and residency requirements for
naturalization.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also said Perez-Portes suffers from a life-threatening
medical condition after suffering a heart attack in 1988 and is
plagued by gland tumors, severe hypertension and Conn's Syndrome, a
condition requiring drugs that might be unavailable in the
Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said he was ''very pleased that justice was done here,
particularly for a former Marine who received a medal for battling
in the front lines in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He volunteered for the Marine Corps back at a time when many
U.S. citizens attempted to avoid the draft and flee to Canada. As
far as I'm concerned, he's more American than a lot of Americans
were,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-14-00 1936 </TRAILER>
