<HEADLINE> Prosecutors decide not to seek death penalty in wedding shooting case </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) - Bergen County prosecutors said Thursday
they will not seek the death penalty in the case of a New Jersey
businessman accused of killing his ex-girlfriend on the day she was
to marry another man.
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Schwanwede, first assistant Bergen County prosecutor,
told Superior Court Judge William C. Meehan he would file a motion
challenging Agustin Garcia's right to pose a passion-provocation
defense to the Sept. 26, 1999, shooting of Gladys Ricart.
</P>
<P>
   The motion will ask ''whether Garcia is entitled as a matter of
law'' to such a defense, Schwanwede said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, 47, of North Bergen, entered innocent pleas Thursday to
charges of murder, weapons offenses and four counts of child
endangerment in the Ricart slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Ricart, 39, was posing for photographs with her bridal party in
her Ridgefield home before her wedding to James Preston Jr. when,
witnesses say, Garcia burst in, pulled a .38-caliber revolver out
of his briefcase and fired five shots at her.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's lawyers have said they are seriously considering a
heat-of-passion defense, contending that Garcia, who headed several
nonprofit organizations in New York City, believed he and Ricart
were still in a romance until the day of her wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ''The truth is that this is a passion case,'' said Garcia's
brother, Jose Garcia, outside Bergen County Superior Court on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers presented a videotape of Garcia and Ricart
together in a store about 12 hours before her wedding at a recent
news conference, which prompted prosecutors to obtain a gag order
prohibiting all attorneys in the case from speaking with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and Ricart family members have said that Ricart ended
her relationship with Garcia about nine months before the shooting
and that Garcia was stalking her.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Edward Jerejian said attorneys would soon file
motions seeking to suppress a statement Garcia made to police and
other evidence including telephone records and items seized from
his briefcase at the time of his arrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
