<HEADLINE> Lieberman sings and schmoozes on late-night shows  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Armed with a warbling voice and a barrel of
wisecracks, Democratic Vice Presidential candidate Joseph Lieberman
hit the late night talk show circuit Thursday, serenading Conan
O'Brien and bonding with Daily Show host Jon Stewart over their
common Jewish faith.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's genial grin turned mischievous when his story about
singing an old Frank Sinatra standard during his 1988 Senate
campaign prompted O'Brien to invite him to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any chance we can get you to sing 'My Way' for us?'' asked the
comic.
</P>
<P>
   His eyes twinkling, the senator said yes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This, as they say, could be the end of a beautiful vice
presidential candidacy,'' joked Lieberman, as the band - led by
former Bruce Springsteen drummer Max Weinberg - prepared to
accompany him. ''But what a way to go out.''
</P>
<P>
   His rendition was heartfelt but less than tuneful, and
interrupted by frequent self-deprecating cracks.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all respect to the great Sinatra, who I love,'' said the
senator, who has earned plaudits since his selection as Vice
President Al Gore's running mate for his sense of humor and
easygoing manner.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't believe I'm doing this,'' he moaned. ''Here comes the
finish, Conan.''
</P>
<P>
   The number capped an evening of comedy. Lieberman hurried to
O'Brien's studio after taping an appearance with Stewart on the
cable channel Comedy Central's political satire ''The Daily Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ''As the first Jewish American on a major ticket, he'll help
this country build a bridge to the 58th Century,'' Stewart cracked
as he introduced Lieberman, referring to the Jewish calendar, which
marks this year as 5760.
</P>
<P>
   The two high-fived about their shared Jewish faith and Stewart
asked to be invited to Passover dinner at the White House next year
should the Gore-Lieberman ticket win.
</P>
<P>
   ''We say, 'Next year in Washington,''' said Lieberman, playing
on Jews' annual Passover promise to celebrate the following year in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   When Stewart asked what the job of the vice president actually
entails, Lieberman called it ''an important question.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been watching old (Johnny) Carson reruns to judge from Ed
McMahon what I should do,'' answered Lieberman, trying out his
sidekick routine.
</P>
<P>
   Tongue in cheek, he praised O'Brien, who recently celebrated his
show's seventh anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you all know ... that during the seven years you've been
doing this show, America has created 22 million new jobs, crime has
fallen ... and we have the strongest economy in our 224-year
history?'' exulted Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Brien urged Lieberman to come up with a better campaign
slogan than ''Go, Joe, Go!'' which supporters chanted at the
Democratic convention, Lieberman offered a few ideas that played on
his ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   He and Gore, he said, had come up with ''A matzoh ball in every
soup,'' ''Gore-Lieberman. No bull. No pork.'' and ''With malice
toward none, but a little guilt for everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
