<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Teacher Charged, 1st Ld-Writethru,550  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - A teacher accused of sexually abusing
two boys in their beds after their parents' New Year's Eve party
took away the children's faith ''that Mommy and Daddy can protect
them in their own home,'' a prosecutor said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, Steven Nowicki, saw his party invitation as ''the
opportunity to bring to life every parent's nightmare,'' said
Assistant District Attorney Lisa Linsky in her opening statement at
Nowicki's sex abuse trial in Westchester County Court.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney John Mangialardi spoke to the jury only
briefly, asking them to ''keep an open mind,'' and hinting that he
would have an explanation for the prosecution's DNA evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Nowicki, 37, of Hastings-on-Hudson, was a new teacher at Dobbs
Ferry Middle School when the parents of one of his pupils invited
him to an impromptu party on Dec. 31, 1998. ''They wanted him to
feel welcome,'' Linsky said.
</P>
<P>
   He was the last guest to leave, and when he left it was without
saying good-bye and with a wine glass in his hand, the prosecutor
said.
</P>
<P>
   The boys' father, concerned, found Nowicki outside, slumped over
the steering wheel of his idling car as if drunk, Linsky said. But
she suggested that was a ruse, and the trial's first witnesses
testified that Nowicki wasn't drinking heavily at the party.
</P>
<P>
   The father invited Nowicki to ''sleep it off on the couch,'' the
prosecutor said, then went upstairs with his 8- and 10-year-old
sons. But at about 5 a.m., she said, Nowicki stole into the boys'
room, switched off the nightlight and ''orally sodomized and
sexually abused one brother and then the other,'' climbing the
ladder to the top bunk.
</P>
<P>
   He then washed his hands in the bathroom, returned to the boys'
room and ''ostensibly went to sleep'' on the floor, the prosecutor
said.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the parents were ''just footsteps away,'' the
prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   The older boy told his parents what had happened, and they found
Nowicki in their sons' room, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the prosecutor's statement, Nowicki turned in his
seat to watch her and the jurors, keeping his head up through even
the most graphic details.
</P>
<P>
   Linsky said swabs taken from one of the boys' private parts
yielded DNA evidence that pointed to Nowicki. But Mangialardi said
a DNA test ''doesn't show you how it got to where it got.'' He did
not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Linsky said the evidence would also include a signed statement
in which Nowicki said it was ''absolutely possible'' he touched the
boys inappropriately.
</P>
<P>
   ''You will be convinced that this defendant was the man in the
dark who committed this crime against two innocents,'' she told the
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Mangialardi said in an interview that Nowicki, who is free on
$350,000 bail, was ''raring to go.'' He would not say whether the
defendant would testify, though he reminded the jurors that they
may not hold it against him if he doesn't. He said Nowicki has been
unemployed since his arrest, in part because of a court order that
bars him from contact with any children.
</P>
<P>
   Nowicki is accused of sodomy, sexual abuse and endangering
children. If convicted he could be sentenced to up to 25 years in
prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
