<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liebmeran will now talk about senate debates  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Now that his vice presidential debate
schedule has been set, U.S. Sen. Joe Lieberman will begin looking
into the possibility of debating his opponent in the race for U.S.
Senate, his campaign said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Philip Giordano is asking for at least two debates,
including an Oct. 19 face-off in New London that was scheduled
before Lieberman was tapped as Al Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has not committed to any.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't want to commit to something locally and then have it
conflict with a national debate,'' said Dan Gerstein, a Lieberman
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, it was announced that Lieberman will debate
Republican vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney on Oct. 5 in
Danville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Gerstein said Lieberman's campaign now ''will have some
discussions internally and then I imagine some talks with Mr.
Giordano and then something will be decided upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Giordano, the mayor of Waterbury, said he was looking forward to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still think he needs to campaign in the state, but I'm
extremely pleased he will do debates,'' Giordano said. ''That will
give us the opportunity to get our message out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has decided to stay in the Senate race despite running
for vice president, saying he does not want to throw the Democratic
party into the turmoil of choosing a new candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Should he win both races, Lieberman would be forced to resign
his Senate seat. Republican Gov. John G. Rowland would then appoint
a successor. A special election would follow in two years, unless
the General Assembly decided to order one sooner.
</P>
<P>
   In a Quinnipiac College poll taken in July, Lieberman was
favored over Giordano in the Senate race, 71 percent to 14 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-14-00 2035 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000914.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Activate RHP Charles Nagy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Charles Nagy, sidelined since undergoing elbow
surgery in May, was activated Thursday and started the Cleveland
Indians' series finale against the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy made his first start since May 16, going 4 2-3 innings and
leaving with the Indians down 3-0. He gave up three runs and five
hits with three walks and a strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Before having chips in his elbow removed on May 17, Nagy was the
Indians' most durable pitcher the past five years. From 1995-99,
the right-hander posted 15 or more wins each season and made 192
starts without missing a turn in the rotation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
