<HEADLINE> GOP Charges Clinton on Tobacco  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ZUCKERBROD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration has begun exploring
ways to help tobacco farmers, and some Republicans charge it looks
like a political effort to boost support for Al Gore in
tobacco-growing states.
</P>
<P>
   Declining cigarette sales and an increased reliance by companies
on less expensive foreign tobacco has reduced the amount of leaf
U.S. farmers can grow under the federal pricing program.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans from tobacco-growing states say the Clinton
administration is partly to blame because it has pushed for
increased taxes on cigarettes and pursued litigation against
tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''This administration has attacked the tobacco industry, which
includes tobacco farmers, for eight years now,'' said Rep. Ernie
Fletcher, R-Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ed Whitfield, R-Ky., said White House officials told him
they planned to appoint a commission to look at ways to help
tobacco farmers, including possibly buying their tobacco quotas,
which are allotments under the federal-pricing program.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do have it from reliable sources that they're getting ready
to appoint a commission to examine the condition of tobacco farming
and to explore a possible quota buyout plan, which would be
financed by new taxes on cigarettes and the tobacco industry,''
Rep. Ed Whitfield, R-Ky., said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield called the effort ''an election-eve scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert confirmed the administration
has been looking at ''reconciling both our public health goals and
our concerns for communities that rely on growing tobacco.''
However, he said the administration had nothing to announce ''at
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   As vice president, Gore has been a zealous critic of tobacco
companies and staunch anti-smoking advocate. Critics question
Gore's motives, noting he was considered a tobacco farming ally
when representing Tennessee in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republican George W. Bush is favored in most tobacco states, but
several are in play, including Kentucky, Georgia, North Carolina
and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore recently discussed issues affecting tobacco farmers with
Kentucky Gov. Paul Patton, a Democrat who supports ending the
federal-pricing system, said John-Mark Hack, director of Patton's
office of agricultural policy. One idea under consideration is to
end government pricing and buy out tobacco farmers over a 20-year
period, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Doug Hattaway acknowledged the meeting
but said he did not know what was discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Agriculture sources say they attended meetings
with White House officials in recent weeks in which a federal
buyout was discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've met with them a couple of times to explain the program,
so they would have an understanding of how it works and what the
size of the quota is,'' said one official, who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The source said the Clinton administration favors letting a
commission make the decision on whether to offer a buyout.
</P>
<P>
   ''They realize there are a lot of pitfalls if they were to
announce a plan without thinking it through,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Department of Agriculture Farm Service Agency:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.fsa.usda.gov/pas/default.asp
</P>
</TEXT>
