<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Patrol Commander Faulted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The commander of a British army patrol seized by a
renegade army faction in Sierra Leone committed a ''grave mistake''
that allowed his men's capture, and now faces disciplinary action,
the military said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One British paratrooper was killed and more than a dozen others
wounded in a dramatic raid Sunday that freed the six captive
British troops, who had been held for 16 days by a renegade army
faction at a base surrounded by mangrove swamps and jungles. Five
other soldiers from the patrol had been released earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A Ministry of Defense inquiry into the incident found that the
unit's commanding officer, Maj. Alan Marshall of the Royal Irish
Regiment, had made ''an error of professional judgment'' by
diverting from his authorized route on Aug. 25, when the 11-man
patrol was seized.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers were taken hostage by a renegade army gang known as
the West Side Boys after visiting a United Nations unit near the
frontline of fighting between rebels and government troops in the
war-ravaged West African country.
</P>
<P>
   British officials had said earlier they had no idea why the
soldiers had driven into the renegades' territory, in Sierra
Leone's Occra Hills, about 45 miles east of the capital, several
miles from the nearest highway patrolled by U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   It was not specified what disciplinary action the unit's
commander would face, but The Ministry of Defense statement said a
court-martial was not expected.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 British troops are in Sierra Leone, training the
nation's shattered defense force to fight an 9-year-old armed
insurgency by the rebels of the Revolutionary United Front that has
left tens of thousands of civilians dead or deliberately mutilated.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's firefight -- a dawn strike by 150 British
paratroopers backed by helicopter gunships -- 26 members of the West
Side Boys were killed and 18 others, including the faction's
leader, were captured.
</P>
<P>
   Before the raid, British officials feared for the safety of the
hostages, in part because of threats and erratic behavior by the
West Side Boys, who are notorious for lack of discipline,
drunkenness and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   In releasing the results of the investigation, the defense
ministry said overall security arrangements for British troops in
Sierra Leone had been found to be adequate, but that commander of
British forces in the country was reminded that troop movements
should be strictly controlled in such a volatile environment.
</P>
<P>
   Some new details about the patrol's capture emerged in the
defense ministry's report. It said that Marshall, after visiting a
United Nations contingent, had diverted his soldiers to the village
of Magbeni, about 50 miles east of Freetown, an area he thought was
free of renegade militias.
</P>
<P>
   But the British troops instead encounted a group of about 25
militiamen, who had a truck with two machine guns. Caught by
surprise, the patrol was quickly overwhelmed and disarmed. Marshall
was struck during the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The hostages were then taken by boat to the renegades' creekside
base, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior British military official, whose identity was not
disclosed, traveled to Sierra Leone to oversee the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 2116 </TRAILER>
