<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ticket Surcharge Hits Packers Fans  </HEADLINE>
By TODD RICHMOND
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Tradition went head-to-head with
pocketbooks Thursday as Green Bay season-ticket holders struggled
with a surcharge to help pay for renovations at Lambeau Field.
</P>
<P>
   Some called the surcharge a slap in the face to loyal fans who
have backed the team through losing seasons. But few said they
would give up their tickets, family heirlooms for many.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole thing reeks,'' said Arvin Schultz, who faces $5,600
in fees for four tickets to seats on the 30-yard line that his late
father-in-law passed down after three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I think of all those years my dad used them, I'm hurt
this is what we mean by 'feel the tradition,''' said his wife, Judy
Schultz, referring to the stadium's logo. ''We'll find a way to pay
it. We won't give them back.''
</P>
<P>
   The surcharges are part of the Packers' $295 million plan to
revamp the aging stadium. The project calls for 10,000 new seats at
the 43-year-old stadium and an atrium to house the Packer Hall of
Fame and other amenities the team hopes will bring in revenue
year-round.
</P>
<P>
   The team says it needs more money from a revamped stadium to
stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The plan became reality Tuesday when Brown County voters
approved a half-percent sales tax to pay back $160 million in
Lambeau construction loans. The vote divided the community and
bruised its famed love affair with the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers expect to raise $92.5 million through the one-time
seat fees once details for the payments are finalized.
</P>
<P>
   Fans with three-game packages will pay $600 per ticket. Fans
like the Schultzes with seven-game packages will pay $1,400 per
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's absolutely gouging,'' Arvin Schultz said.
</P>
<P>
   John Jones, Packers vice president of administration, said seat
fees are a common fundraising tactic in the NFL. He stressed the
fees were one-time assessments.
</P>
<P>
   ''The organization is very mindful of the effect of costs on
ticket holders,'' he said. ''But we're part of an industry in the
NFL where costs continue to escalate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 2154 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000914.0182 </DOCNO>
