<HEADLINE> FBI called to investigate civil rights violations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ELMIRA, N.Y. (AP) - The Federal Bureau of Investigation will
look into charges that city police violated the civil rights of
teen-agers involved in a melee earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   More than six complaints have been filed, all by
African-American teen-agers, police said. A police union spokesman
said charges of racism were ''wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was total havoc,'' said Patrick Sullivan. ''For them to say
it was because the youths were mostly black is wrong. We would have
reacted this way if the crowd was Mexican, Chinese, white.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine teen-agers were arrested Sept. 3 after a fight broke out
following an alcohol-free party downtown. With a couple of hundred
people standing around, 15 police officers arrived to quell the
disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   A 14-year-old girl struggled with officers, spitting on them and
biting. When police piled her into a cruiser, she kicked out two
windows.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-year-old boy charged with second-degree harassment,
disorderly conduct and resisting arrest said an officer grabbed him
off his bike and pushed him against a bridge railing, spraying him
with pepper spray when the boy tried to back away.
</P>
<P>
   A police dog bit him on the leg as he knelt on the sidewalk in
handcuffs, the boy said.
</P>
<P>
   Police acknowledge using pepper spray but said the dog was kept
on a leash and ordered to attack only when a pair of officers were
being stomped. None of the officers received injuries that kept
them out of work.
</P>
<P>
   A timetable for the FBI probe was not given.
</P>
</TEXT>
