<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Mayoral Race Picks Up Steam  </HEADLINE>
By JUDY LIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- While the presidential candidates haggled
over their debate schedule Thursday, mayoral hopefuls in Los
Angeles cordially held their eighth debate -- seven months before
the election.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the five leading candidates squared off over police
corruption and urban environmental issues with none of the
squabbling that had, until Thursday, stymied efforts to get Al Gore
and George W. Bush together.
</P>
<P>
   The quartet included two Hispanic lawmakers, a city councilman
and a businessman. If voters elect a Hispanic in April, it will
mark the first Hispanic mayor in the nonpartisan office in 129
years.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan is unable to run again due to term limits.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department has been under fire since allegations
surfaced that anti-gang officers lied under oath, falsified
reports, planted evidence and even shot unarmed suspects. Law
enforcement was a top issue at the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe it's humanly possible for people to look at
themselves objectively,'' Councilman Joel Wachs said in urging
outside help to clean up the department.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tell you, the Police Department is not going to reform
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   All four candidates agreed that Police Chief Bernard Parks
should be held accountable for the department's failures, but urged
caution in acting too quickly and were vague about what should be
done. Three advocated a consent decree with the U.S. government
because they believe the department has failed to reform itself.
</P>
<P>
   City officials have been debating whether the city should sign
the consent decree that would call for a judge to monitor the
department and ensure reforms are carried out. The Justice
Department would, in exchange, drop a planned lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''By opposing the consent decree, we're saying 'go ahead sue
me,''' said Rep. Xavier Becerra, a Los Angeles Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Antonio Villaraigosa also favored the consent
decree.
</P>
<P>
   ''This city needs to move beyond the crisis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Businessman Steve Soboroff, Riordan's choice for mayor, opposed
the consent decree. He said crime would rise as officers leave the
streets to process paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   City Attorney James Hahn was the only major candidate who didn't
appear. He said he had a scheduling conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 2217 </TRAILER>
