<HEADLINE> Taylor To Step Down at Boston Globe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Stephen E. Taylor, executive vice president of The
Boston Globe and a direct descendant of the family that ran the
newspaper for generations, will step down on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor announced Thursday that he plans to pursue a variety of
opportunities in the field of new media. In a letter to staffers,
Taylor said he plans to continue to consult for The Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor joined The Globe in 1980 and became assistant business
manager in 1986. He was named a vice president in 1991, executive
vice president in 1993 and became president of the electronic
publishing unit in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He oversees the paper's operations, production, technology and
administrative services. He also helped create The Boston Globe
Electronic Publishing Co. in 1994, and The Globe's Web site,
www.boston.com.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's family owned and led The Globe for five generations
until it was purchased by The New York Times in the late 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
