<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aikman Not Sure of Playing Status  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Not even Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy
Aikman is sure of his playing status.
</P>
<P>
   After practicing for the second time since missing Sunday
night's game at Arizona because of a concussion, Aikman said he
felt good but didn't know if he would play Monday night at
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to be a little more committal on what I'm going to be
able to do ... I don't know. I really don't know,'' Aikman said
after practice Thursday. ''It's something we're taking a lot of
time in deciding and trying to make a decision on this thing and
it's not easy. It's not real clear-cut and black and white.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman suffered his ninth career concussion -- and third in 10
regular-season starts -- in the season-opening 41-14 loss to
Philadelphia. He missed two games last season after concussions in
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Thursday if he still had headaches or any other
lingering affects from the latest concussion, Aikman provided an
evasive answer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not at liberty to discuss some of the things that I've
experienced or haven't experienced or where I'm at with all of
those things,'' Aikman said. ''Those are things being discussed
with the doctors, and that evaluation process is obviously the
reason why we haven't come to a clear-cut answer yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has split snaps in practice this week with Randall
Cunningham, who completed 24 of 34 passes for 243 yards and two
touchdowns Sunday night in Dallas' 32-31 loss to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, 33, admitted to treating this concussion differently
than others he has had.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's probably partly true and I think last year is what
initiated that,'' he said. ''I think because of what took place
last year is why there's extra caution. And then in addition to
that, probably my age and my stage in my career has instigated a
lot of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
