<HEADLINE> Police seize 150 bombs from house  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WEBSTER, N.Y. (AP) - Police removed 150 homemade bombs and 20
guns Thursday from a suburban house after evacuating neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Police staked out Jack Roessel's house after learning a company
had sent the man five pounds of potassium perchlorate, a chemical
that can be used in explosives, on Sept. 5. The federal Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms joined local and state police in the
raid Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Roessel, 41, is charged with two counts of criminal possession
of a weapon and first degree reckless endangerment, both class D
felonies.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were five kids within a tenth of a mile waiting to get
on a school bus,'' State Police Capt. Mark Fischer told the
Democrat and Chronicle of Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Had the explosives detonated, with the equivalent power of 18
pounds of TNT, the children ''would have been killed,'' Fischer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Roessel probably didn't intend to hurt anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ''He tells us he likes to see things explode,'' Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the guns found, p[olice recovered a AR-15 assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Roessel was jailed in lieu of $10,000 bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
