<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Strikes at Gore on Fund Raising  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, Calif. (AP) -- George W. Bush, trying to regain the
offensive against Democratic rival Al Gore, said Thursday the vice
president ''may have crossed a serious line'' on campaign fund
raising, reviving questions about whether Gore can be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   ''The appearance is really disturbing,'' Bush said by satellite
to a conference of the National Guard Association of the United
States. ''I will restore the bond of trust between the president
and all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in weeks, Bush was prodding Gore to react to
a controversy, rather than being thrown off-stride himself by
developments.
</P>
<P>
   Documents being reviewed by the Justice Department indicate Gore
was asked to make a fund-raising phone call in 1995 to a Texas
trial lawyer involved in tobacco industry litigation. The lawyer
and his firm later gave $790,000 to the Democratic Party after
President Clinton vetoed a bill to limit liability lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore aide said the vice president never made the phone call.
But Bush pounced on the issue, which recalled other queries into
such matters as Gore's fund raising at a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   ''It sounded like on the surface there's a quid pro quo,'' Bush
said in an interview with KTTV-TV in Los Angeles, citing newspaper
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ''Americans are tired of investigations and scandal, and the
best way to get rid of them is to elect a new president who will
bring a new administration, who will restore honor and dignity to
the White House,'' Bush said to the National Guard group. ''I have
done so as governor of Texas. I will do so as president of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign said Bush was trying to distract voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''George Bush has become desperate,'' said Gore spokeswoman Kym
Spell. ''Instead of talking about the issues, Bush is dredging up
ancient allegations that have nothing to do with this election,
tired old personal attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had some distractions himself. After balking for weeks at a
three-debate proposal by Gore and the Commission on Presidential
Debates, Bush gave in Thursday and agreed to that plan.
</P>
<P>
   And spokeswoman Karen Hughes said a mystery package received
Wednesday by the Gore campaign was, indeed, authentic footage of
Bush practicing his debate style and strategy -- political gold if
his opponent had studied it. But the man who received it in the
mail, Gore adviser Tom Downey, said he didn't watch much of it and
instead turned it over to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign clearly reveled in the chance to try to put Gore
on the defensive and to allow the Republican to focus on his own
issues rather than answering daily queries about messages buried in
ads or why Gore has gained in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Bush campaign released an ad intended to
complement a Republican National Committee spot assailing Gore on
Social Security, education and tax cuts. Called ''Compare,'' Bush's
ad is scheduled to run in 18 states beginning Friday, while the
party's spot began running Wednesday in seven states.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Gore? He says he wants to fight for the people against
HMOs, but his prescription drug plan forces seniors into one HMO
selected by the federal government,'' an announcer says in the
party ad.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Bush ad says Gore's plan ''forces seniors into a
government-run HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than indulge reporters' questions about strategy, Bush
stuck to his subjects of choice in California, education reform and
military readiness. Polls show Gore ahead in the state, but Bush
says he is going to compete hard here.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to students at Santa Ana High School, he reiterated his
plan to make schools more accountable for student performance and
to give local and state governments more flexibility to spend
education money as they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Students of this heavily Hispanic school peppered him with
questions on other topics, such as whether he supports the teaching
of sexual abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   He replied: ''I think it's very important for our children to
understand the power and promise of abstinence education.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrapping up his trip to California, Bush was stopping in New
Mexico on Friday before heading home to Texas for the weekend. He
was to visit battleground states in the Midwest and Florida next
week, including a stop in Chicago Tuesday for the Oprah Winfrey
Show and one in New York for the ''Live with Regis'' show on
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
