<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bermuda issues Florence watch; new depression forms off Yucatan  </HEADLINE>
By ADRIAN SAINZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) - Tropical Storm Florence showed signs Thursday
afternoon of making its promised eastward move in the Atlantic
Ocean, prompting storm watches in Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new tropical depression formed in the western
Caribbean with a forecast track eventually taking it into the Gulf
of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Florence probably will resume an eastward track by early Friday
toward Bermuda, where the island's weather service issued a storm
watch Thursday. Florence was briefly a hurricane Tuesday before
degenerating to a tropical storm Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Florence could brush Bermuda with tropical storm-force winds and
give it drenching rains and a pounding surf by Friday evening, said
forecasters at the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it follows the forecast track, then they will be right on
the edge,'' said Richard Pasch, a hurricane specialist. ''They
could get wind gusts of up above 40 miles per hour.''
</P>
<P>
   At 11 p.m. EDT, Florence, still nearly stationary, was centered
near latitude 29.2 north, longitude 73.0 west, or about 535 miles
west-southwest of Bermuda. Moving southeast at nearly 3 mph,
Florence had maximum sustained winds reaching 45 mph. It was
expected to begin trekking eastward by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The depression off Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula in the western
Caribbean could remain over the peninsula before entering the
south-central Gulf of Mexico sometime Friday, said Eric Blake, a
hurricane center meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
   If the center survives the trip over the Yucatan - and it's
small enough that it may not survive - intensification into a
tropical storm is likely over the warm waters of the Gulf of
Mexico, Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was too early to know which track the depression would
take if it makes it into the Gulf, Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane hunter aircraft flew into the depression Thursday
morning and found its center near latitude 20.0 north and longitude
87.5 west, moving to the northwest near 10 mph with sustained winds
near 30 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rip currents associated with Florence and blamed for
at least two surf deaths Tuesday in North Carolina were expected to
continue. Rescue workers searched a second day for a 23-year-old
man missing after falling out of a kayak, but did not find him.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they do not intend to reopen the two beaches
until Florence is no longer a threat.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-14-00 2311 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000914.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Jays 3, Yankees 2, 11 Innings  </HEADLINE>
By JOSH DUBOW
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Jose Cruz Jr. hit a two-run homer in the 11th
inning as the Toronto Blue Jays beat the New York Yankees 3-2
Thursday night despite David Wells again failing to become the
first 20-game winner in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   In a pitchers' duel full of postseason intensity, Wells and Andy
Pettitte matched zeros for seven innings, yet neither was around
when the game was decided.
</P>
<P>
   With the score 1-all, Carlos Delgado led off the 11th with a
walk against Randy Choate (0-1). Two outs later, Cruz hit a drive
into the wind in left field. Luis Polonia backed up to the wall,
leaped, but the ball just cleared his glove for Cruz's 30th homer.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz joined Delgado, Tony Batista and Brad Fullmer with 30
homers, making Toronto and this year's Anaheim Angels as the only
AL teams with four 30-homer hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Koch (8-3) pitched two innings for the win and Kelvim
Escobar pitched the 11th for his second save, allowing a one-out
homer to Ryan Thompson. The Blue Jays moved within three games of
wild card leader Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who allowed eight hits and no walks in eight innings,
failed for the third time to reach 20 wins for the first time in
his career. He got knocked out in the second inning against Oakland
on Sept. 4, and Koch blew a 5-4 lead in the ninth for Wells last
Saturday against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   After Pettitte's throwing error led to an unearned run in the
top of the eighth, Wells appeared to be on his way to winning No.
20 in his favorite stadium and in front of the fans who adored him
during his two years in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Derek Jeter tied the game in the bottom half when hit a shot
over the center-field fence for his 14th homer. Wells slapped in
disgust as plate umpire Angel Hernandez threw out a new ball,
watching another chance at 20 wins go by. Wells probably will get
three more starts.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, going for his 100th career win, didn't allow a runner
past first base until Craig Grebeck led off the eighth with a
double. Alberto Castillo then bunted back to Pettitte who wheeled
and threw to third. The wild throw sailed into left field, scoring
pinch-runner Dewayne Wise and sending Castillo to second on the
error.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Stewart followed with another bunt to Pettitte, who
struggled to pick the ball up before throwing to first. The throw
appeared to beat Stewart, but umpire Marty Foster called him safe,
sending manager Joe Torre barreling out of the dugout. Torre was
ejected in the argument.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte left after a sacrifice bunt by Alex Gonzalez, and Mike
Stanton got out of the jam without additional damage. Pettitte
allowed four hits in 7 1-3 innings, striking out nine.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees nearly lost it in the 10th when reliever Jeff Nelson
made a boneheaded play on a bunt. With a runner on first and one
out, Gonzalez popped it back to Nelson, who let the ball drop to
try for a double play. Nelson threw to first, and the speedy
Stewart to reach second without a play.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson recovered to strike out Dave Martinez and sprinted back
to the dugout in relief.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Wells walked none in 13 of 32 starts. ... Wells is 28-9
with a 3.27 ERA in his career at Yankee Stadium. ... Jeter singled
in the first and has reached base safely in 39 straight games -- the
longest active streak in the majors. ... Delgado, third in the AL
with 39 homers, went 1-for-4 with three strikeouts and has a
15-game homerless stretch -- tied for his longest of the season. ...
Torre has been ejected twice this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 2312 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000914.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drugs, as Always, an Olympic Issue  </HEADLINE>
By OWEN CANFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- As preparations for the Olympics
entered their final hours, a prestigious science journal questioned
drug-testing efforts and a royal member of the IOC said the games
may never be drug free.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the Thursday issue of ''Nature'' said some
athletes will still get away with using human growth hormone.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although the scientists developing the tests are confident
that they could have been readied in time for Sydney, the IOC
refused to sanction funding for the necessary validation studies,''
the journal said. ''As a result, unscrupulous athletes know that
they can abuse hGH with impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Princess Anne, president of the British Olympic Association and
an International Olympic Committee member, said the temptation for
world-class athletes to gain an edge through performance-enhancing
drugs would always be too great.
</P>
<P>
   ''You will never defeat it entirely,'' she said in an interview
with Britain's ITN. ''It is a problem that will always be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Francois Carrard, IOC director general, said that as of Friday,
the IOC had conducted 269 out-of-competition tests and 149 controls
for the hormone EPO, with no positive results. EPO raises the level
of oxygen-carrying red blood cells and is favored by endurance
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Romanian delegation withdrew weightlifter Traian
Ciharean from the competition following reports he was caught
doping. Media reports said Ciharean tested positive for a
prohibited substance in an out-of-competition test in July. No
further details were available.
</P>
<P>
   Human growth hormone, which was designed to treat dwarfism, is
used by some athletes to build muscle. In January 1999, a
consortium headed by London endocrinologist Peter Sonksen told the
IOC it had found a ''very credible test'' for hGH.
</P>
<P>
   Sonksen said validation studies would cost about $5 million,
which the IOC called too high and declined to fund.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also found flaws in the IOC's tests for EPO, saying
any athlete who stopped taking EPO a few days before their event
''will probably test negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a positive blood test would not mean punishment since the
IOC requires two failed tests.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the International Olympic Committee and other sports
governing bodies do not provide more funding to back their tough
words on drugs ... scientists say they will continue to be
runners-up in the doping contest,'' the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCaffrey, head of the White House drug office and a
critic of drug-testing methods in sports, said he isn't satisfied
with the EPO test but that, ''It's a valid effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The current test will have an ''enormously reassuring effect on
the many honest athletes who wanted to come here and compete,''
McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   German swimmer Franziska van Almsick, winner of three medals at
the Atlanta Olympics, questioned the will of sports to control
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have the impression that not everybody 100 percent wants
something to be done about it,'' she told the financial daily
Handelsblatt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the coach of the Chinese rowing team insisted his
athletes have not used EPO, even though seven members failed the
test. Zhang Quing suggested traditional medicines might be to
blame.
</P>
<P>
   He said if Chinese authorities had used the combined blood and
urine test being employed at Sydney to check for use of the
performance-enhancing substance, all of his rowers would have been
cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ''They definitely did not use EPO,'' Zhang said Thursday. ''If
they had used the full EPO tests, not one of our athletes would
have been positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The rowers were dropped after the blood test, which Zhang said
showed they had above-normal red blood-cell counts. In all, China
dropped 27 athletes, most for failing blood tests for EPO.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang said nutritional supplements might have affected the
tests. He also said some rowers take Chinese medicines typically
given to women after childbirth to boost their blood cell counts.
</P>
<P>
   A Greek athlete who was stopped Saturday for carrying a natural
drug that is banned in Australia arrived in Sydney to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Triple jump champion Stamatis Lenis, 22, and coach Stavrou
Zougouridis were stopped by customs officers in Perth for carrying
the natural Russian drug Ekdisten.
</P>
<P>
   Tests conducted in Canberra revealed the drug contained
Ecdysterone, a natural substance used to aid an athlete's recovery.
The drug is outlawed in Australia but isn't banned by the IOC as a
performance-enhancing drug.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek team announced that Lenis had been given the go-ahead
to compete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-14-00 2314 </TRAILER>
