<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One hurt when police boat smashes rowing scull  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) - A 13-year-old was seriously
injured Thursday afternoon when the rowing scull she was in was
struck by a police patrol boat.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the Saratoga County Sheriff's boat piloted by
Deputy Richard Lawrence was moving fast over Saratoga Lake when it
struck the rowing scull broadside at 4:35 p.m. Nine junior high and
high school girls were aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the area where the accident happened was
posted as a ''no-wake zone'' to slow boats down.
</P>
<P>
   Maya Hensley-Lapham, the most seriously injured, was being
treated at Albany Medical Center Hospital for a broken pelvis and
broken ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Witness Dave Bronner said it was lucky more people weren't hurt.
The 63-foot long boat was broken in half.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really dodged a big bullet out on Saratoga Lake today,''
Bronner told The Saratogian. ''I can't believe the propeller on
that big outboard motor didn't get those girls. There was Fiberglas
all over the place. He was really moving.''
</P>
<P>
   State Park Police are investigating the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Falvo, 13, the coxswain aboard the scull, said she had
the rowers change course to try to avoid the collision. She thinks
Lawrence saw her but too late to change direction.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he saw me, he turned really hard, but it was too late,''
she said. ''He was going too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The glare of the sun may have played a role in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga Springs is 30 miles north of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-14-00 2324 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
