<DOCNO> APW20000914.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-San Francisco Mayor Dies  </HEADLINE>
By RON HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- George Christopher, the former San
Francisco mayor who persuaded the New York Giants to move to the
West Coast, died Thursday of a stroke. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher was the city's 34th mayor and served in office from
1956-64. He was the last Republican mayor of San Francisco and
retired from politics arena after finishing behind Ronald Reagan in
the 1966 California governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher's tenure as mayor was highlighted when he convinced
the New York Giants to move to San Francisco after the 1957 season.
He was also instrumental in getting Candlestick Park built amid the
chilly, swirling winds along the San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   He was teased later by colleagues about the poor weather
conditions at Candlestick Point, but Christopher was remembered
fondly Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''San Francisco has suffered a monumental loss following this
morning's death of former mayor George Christopher,'' current mayor
Willie Brown said in a statement. ''George was a dear friend and he
will be deeply missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Born George Christopheles in Arcadia, Greece on Dec. 8, 1907,
Christopher was brought to San Francisco when he was 2 years old.
He went on to earn a degree in accounting from the Golden Gate
Night College and became a citizen of the United States in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher began his political career serving on the San
Francisco Board of Supervisors in 1945. Ten years later he was
elected mayor by the largest majority in the city's history at that
time.
</P>
<P>
   During Christopher's mayoral terms, Fortune Magazine called San
Francisco ''one of the best administered cities in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has ordered the city's flags flown at half-staff to
commemorate Christopher's life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
