<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Case Can Be Heard in U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A lawsuit accusing the Royal Dutch Petroleum Co.
of assisting in the torture and murder of Nigerian activists can be
heard in federal court in New York rather than England, an appeals
court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Brown Chomsky, the lead lawyer for the plaintiffs, called
the ruling from the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals a
''significant victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the defendants, Royal Dutch Petroleum Co.,
incorporated in the Netherlands, and Shell Transport and Trading
Co., incorporated in Great Britain, did not return telephone
messages.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies jointly control and operate the Royal
Dutch/Shell Group, an international network of affiliated but
formally independent oil and gas companies, according to the ruling
from Judge Pierre Leval.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs alleged in a lawsuit in federal court in New York
that one of the affiliated companies, Shell Petroleum Development
Co. of Nigeria Limited, coercively took land for oil development
without adequate compensation and polluted air and water in the
Ogoni region of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   They said Shell Nigeria recruited the Nigerian police and
military to attack local villages and suppress the organized
opposition to its development projects.
</P>
<P>
   One plaintiff sued on behalf of his father and another on behalf
of her husband after both men were hanged, along with Ogoni
leaders, in 1995 after being convicted of murder by a special
military tribunal on charges that the lawsuit alleged were based on
fabricated evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Another plaintiff alleged he was illegally detained by Nigerian
authorities while a fourth said she was beaten and shot by the
Nigerian military in a raid on her village.
</P>
<P>
   It reversed a decision by U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood in
Manhattan that concluded the case should be tried in England. The
appeals court said Wood failed to properly consider the importance
of letting a U.S. resident choose where the trial occurs and
interests of the United States in litigating alleged human rights
violations.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court praised British courts but said the defendants
had failed to prove that ''pertinent factors tilt sufficiently
strongly in favor of trial in the foreign forum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
