<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Cons Show Up At Job Fair  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- About 3,300 ex-convicts showed up at the
Cleveland Convention Center this week for what organizers believe
was the nation's first job fair for people with criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies ran out of application forms in the first hour.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a great opportunity,'' said DeLorese Pearson, 27,
convicted of child endangerment. In less than three months of
freedom, ''I have filled out hundreds of applications, and no one
has called me.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Parker, 39, who served time for robbery and related
crimes, said he wants a job to help him raise his children and
inspire them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got to show them the initiative and the will to make my own
way. At the moment, I'll settle for anything, just to be part of
society again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The job fair was organized mainly by federal, state, Cuyahoga
County and Cleveland officials supervising more than 15,000 former
offenders. About 40 employers attended Wednesday's fair, along with
40 social service agencies helping the former offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people have gone through the correction system and paid
their debt to society and would make good employees,'' said
Elizabeth Vechter, United Parcel Service employment manager for
northern Ohio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
